rld Economic Forum 2013.jpg\n| birth_name         = Azim Hashim Premji\n| caption            = Premji in 2013\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1945|7|24}}\n| birth_place        = [[Bombay]], [[Bombay presidency]], [[British India]]<ref name=ebr>{{cite news|title=Azim Premji|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/710892/Azim-Premji|accessdate=26 December 2013|work=Britannica}}</ref>\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| parents            = Mohamed Hashem Premji\n| spouse             = Yasmeen\n| children           = [[Rishad Premji]], Tariq<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/getahead/2007/jun/07rishad.htm|title=What you didn't know about Rishad Premji|date=7 June 2007|publisher=Rediff|accessdate=7 December 2009}}</ref>\n| alma_mater         = [[Stanford University]] ([[Bachelor of Engineering|B.S.E]])<ref name=forbesbill>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2009/10/billionaires-2009-richest-people_Azim-Premji_1UFS.html|title=The World's Billionaires No. 83 Azim Premji|date=3 November 2009|work=Forbes|accessdate=7 December 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091129090553/http://www.forbes.com/lists/2009/10/billionaires-2009-richest-people_Azim-Premji_1UFS.html| archivedate= 29 November 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n| occupation         = Chairman of [[Wipro]]\n| networth           = [[US$]]7.2 billion (October 2019)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/azim-premji/|title=Azim Premji's profile at Forbes|accessdate=25 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| website            = {{URL|https://www.wipro.com/leadership/azim-h-premji/|Azim Premji at Wipro}}\n| signature          = Signature of Azim Premji.svg\n}}\n\n'''Azim Hashim Premji''' (born 24 July 1945) is an Indian [[Business magnate|business tycoon]], [[investor]], [[engineer]], and [[philanthropist]], who is the chairman of [[Wipro Limited]]. He is informally known as the Czar of the Indian IT Industry.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.entrepreneurssolutions.com/top-10-entrepreneurs-in-india-1-penchal-reddy-born13th-march-1990residencesingapore-nationalityindianyears-active-years-active-2012-to-presentqualificati/ |title=Top 10 Entrepreneurs of India |date=30 August 2015 |author=Bhupathi Reddy |publisher=EntrepreneurSolutions.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160126161619/https://www.entrepreneurssolutions.com/top-10-entrepreneurs-in-india-1-penchal-reddy-born13th-march-1990residencesingapore-nationalityindianyears-active-years-active-2012-to-presentqualificati/ |archivedate=26 January 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mybtechlife.com/the-list-of-great-entrepreneurs-in-india-2015/ |title=The List of Great Entrepreneurs of India in 2015 |publisher=MyBTechLife |author=Srikar Muthyala |date=29 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160114000446/http://mybtechlife.com/the-list-of-great-entrepreneurs-in-india-2015/ |archivedate=14 January 2016 }}</ref> He was responsible for guiding Wipro through four decades of diversification and growth to finally emerge as one of the global leaders in the software industry.<ref name=\"Forbes.com\">[https://www.forbes.com/profile/azim-premji/ Azim Premji Profile] Forbes.com. Retrieved September 2010.</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2009/10/billionaires-2009-richest-people_Azim-Premji_1UFS.html|title=The World's Billionaires|date=3 March 2009|work=Forbes|accessdate=16 March 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090316053019/http://www.forbes.com/lists/2009/10/billionaires-2009-richest-people_Azim-Premji_1UFS.html| archivedate= 16 March 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> In 2010, he was voted among the 20 most powerful men in the world by [[Asiaweek]]. He has twice been listed among the 100 most influential people by [[TIME Magazine]], once in 2004 and more recently in 2011.<ref>Gates, Bill. (21 April 2011) [http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,2066367_2066369_2066101,00.html Azim Premji \u2013 The 2011 TIME 100]. TIME. Retrieved on 12 November 2011.</ref>\n\nHe is currently the tenth richest person in India with an estimated net worth of US$7.2 billion as of October 2019. In 2013, he agreed to give away at least half of his wealth by signing [[The Giving Pledge]]. Premji started with a $2.2 billion donation to the Azim Premji Foundation, focused on education in India.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/naazneenkarmali/2013/02/23/azim-premji-donates-2-3-billion-after-signing-giving-pledge/#59a8169024cd|title=Azim Premji Donates $2.3 Billion After Signing Giving Pledge|last=Karmali|first=Naazneen|work=Forbes|access-date=22 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nPremji was born in [[Bombay]], [[India]] in a Muslim family.<ref name=\"ebr\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldofceos.com/dossiers/azim-premji|title=Azim Premji|publisher=Worldofceos.com|accessdate=26 December 2013}}</ref> His father was a noted businessman and was known as ''Rice King of Burma''. [[Muhammad Ali Jinnah]], founder of [[Pakistan]], invited his father Muhammed Hashem Premji to come to Pakistan, he turned down the request and chose to remain in India.<ref name=bp>{{cite web|title=Billionaire Profile: Azim Premji by Mandovi Menon|url=http://www.mensxp.com/work-life/leadership/10244-billionaire-profile-azim-premji.html|publisher=MENSXP.COM|accessdate=1 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nPremji has a Bachelor of Science in Electrical Engineering degree from [[Stanford University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wipro.com/leadership/azim-h-premji/|title=Wipro Leadership \u2013 Azim Premji|access-date=15 July 2019}}</ref> He is married to Yasmeen. The couple have two children, Rishad and Tariq. Rishad is currently the Chief Strategy Officer of IT Business, Wipro.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/2010/09/03/stories/2010090352040700.htm|title=Rishad Premji is Wipro's new CSO|date=2 September 2010|work=The Hindu |accessdate=10 September 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100908083431/http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/2010/09/03/stories/2010090352040700.htm| archivedate= 8 September 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn 1945, Muhammed Hashim Premji incorporated Western Indian Vegetable Products Ltd, based at Amalner, a small town in the Jalgaon district of Maharashtra. It used to manufacture cooking oil under the brand name Sunflower Vanaspati, and a laundry soap called 787, a byproduct of oil manufacture.<ref>[http://churumuri.wordpress.com/2009/07/20/when-azim-premjis-father-said-no-and-no-again/ Western Indian Products Ltd incorporated in 1945]. Churumuri.wordpress.com (20 July 2009). Retrieved on 21 November 2015.</ref> In 1966, on the news of his father's death, the then 21-year-old Azim Premji returned home from [[Stanford University]], where he was studying engineering, to take charge of [[Wipro]]. The company, which was called Western Indian Vegetable Products at the time, dealt in hydrogenated oil manufacturing but Azim Premji later diversified the company to bakery fats, ethnic ingredient based toiletries, hair care soaps, baby toiletries, lighting products, and hydraulic cylinders. In the 1980s, the young entrepreneur, recognising the importance of the emerging [[Information technology|IT]] field, took advantage of the vacuum left behind by the expulsion of [[IBM]] from India, changed the company name to ''Wipro'' and entered the high-technology sector by manufacturing minicomputers under technological collaboration with an American company Sentinel<ref>[http://www.sentinel.com/ Home Page \u2013 Sentinel Technologies, Inc]. Sentinel.com. Retrieved on 21 November 2015.</ref> Computer Corporation.<ref>Chakravarty, 1998:2</ref> Thereafter Premji made a focused shift from soaps to software.<ref>[http://www.iloveindia.com/indian-heroes/azim-premji.html Azim Premji Profile \u2013 Biography of Azim Premji \u2013 Information on Azeem Premji Wipro Technologies]. Iloveindia.com (24 July 1945). Retrieved on 12 November 2011.</ref>\n\n===Recognition===\nPremji has been recognised by Business Week as one of the ''Greatest Entrepreneurs'' for being responsible for Wipro emerging as one of the world's fastest growing companies.<ref>[http://www.ibtimes.co.in/articles/20070704/wipro-chief-features-in-business-week-30-greatest-entrepreneurs-of-all-time-list.htm Wipro Ltd chief features in Business Week's \"30 Greatest Entrepreneurs of all Time\" list] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090705133216/http://www.ibtimes.co.in/articles/20070704/wipro-chief-features-in-business-week-30-greatest-entrepreneurs-of-all-time-list.htm|date=5 July 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, he was conferred an honorary doctorate by the [[Manipal Academy of Higher Education]]. In 2006, Azim Premji was awarded Lakshya Business Visionary by [[National Institute of Industrial Engineering]], Mumbai.<ref>[http://www.financialexpress.com/news/indias-best-business-minds-converge-at-nities-lakshya/181593/0 Azim Premji awarded by E]. Financialexpress.com (22 October 2006). Retrieved on 12 November 2011.</ref> In 2009, he was awarded an honorary doctorate from [[Wesleyan University]] in Middletown, [[Connecticut]] for his outstanding philanthropic work.<ref>[http://roth.blogs.wesleyan.edu/2010/01/08/studying-abroad/?ref_homepage Roth on Wesleyan \u00bb Blog Archive \u00bb Studying Abroad]. Roth.blogs.wesleyan.edu (8 January 2010). Retrieved on 12 November 2011.</ref> In 2015, [[Mysore University]] conferred an honorary doctorate on him.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/karnataka/mysore-varsity-doctorate-for-premji-bhyrappa-nagathihalli-chandrashekar/article7107690.ece|title=Mysore varsity doctorate for Premji, Bhyrappa, Nagathihalli Chandrashekar}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, the Government of India honoured him with the title of [[Padma Bhushan]] for his outstanding work in trade and commerce.<ref name=\"Padma Awards\">{{cite web|url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |title=Padma Awards |publisher=Ministry of Home Affairs, Government of India |date=2015 |accessdate=21 July 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151015193758/http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |archivedate=15 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, he has been awarded [[Padma Vibhushan]], the second highest civilian award by the Government of India.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Padma Awards Announced|url=http://www.pib.nic.in/newsite/erelease.aspx?relid=69364|publisher=[[Ministry of Home Affairs (India)|Ministry of Home Affairs]] |date=25 January 2011|accessdate=25 January 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2017, [[India Today]] magazine ranked him 9th in India's 50 Most powerful people of 2017 list.<ref>{{cite news|title=India's 50 powerful people|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/india-today-top-50-powerful-indians-mukesh-ambani-ratan-tata-kumar-mangalam-birla-gautam-adani-anand-mahindra-srk-amitabh-bacchan/1/928939.html|publisher=[[India Today]]|date=14 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Philanthropy==\n===Azim Premji Foundation===\nIn 2001, he founded Azim Premji Foundation,a non-profit organization.<ref>[http://azimpremjifoundation.org/ Azim Premji Foundation]. Azim Premji Foundation. Retrieved on 28 July 2013.</ref>\n\nIn December 2010, he pledged to donate US$2 billion for improving school education in India. This has been done by transferring 213 million equity shares of Wipro Ltd, held by a few entities controlled by him, to the Azim Premji Trust. This donation is the largest of its kind in India. In March 2019, Premji pledged an additional 34% of [[Wipro]] stock held by him to the foundation. At a current value of about US$7.5 billion, this allocation will bring the total endowment from him to the foundation to US$21 billion.<ref>{{cite news|author=Arnab Paul |title=Wipro Chairman Premji pledges 34 percent of company shares for philanthropy |url=https://in.reuters.com/article/us-wipro-premji-idINKBN1QU21H |agency=Reuters |location=Bengaluru, India |date= 13 March 2019 |access-date= 14 March 2019 }}</ref>\n\nThe foundation has warned against [[scam emails]] which claim to be from the foundation and falsely request donations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://azimpremjifoundation.org/alerts-online-scams-fradulent-mails|title=Alerts on online scams and fraudulent mails|last=|first=|date=|website=Azim Premji Foundation|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref>\n\n===The Giving Pledge===\nPremji has said that being rich \"did not thrill\" him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://epaper.indianexpress.com/c/11343877|title=Clipping of Indian Express \u2013 Chandigarh|access-date=29 June 2016}}</ref> He became the first Indian to sign up for [[The Giving Pledge]], a campaign led by [[Warren Buffett]] and [[Bill Gates]], to encourage the wealthiest people to make a commitment to give most of their wealth to philanthropic causes. He is the third non-American after [[Richard Branson]] and [[David Sainsbury]] to join this philanthropy club.<ref>{{cite news|title=Azim Premji donates half of his wealth|url=http://www.in.com/news/business/azim-premji-donates-half-of-his-wealth-50187456-in-1.html|accessdate=20 February 2013|date=20 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130310062218/http://www.in.com/news/business/azim-premji-donates-half-of-his-wealth-50187456-in-1.html|archive-date=10 March 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n:\"I strongly believe that those of us, who are privileged to have wealth, should contribute significantly to try and create a better world for the millions who are far less privileged\"--- Azim Premji (AP)\n\nIn April 2013 he said that he has already given more than 25 per cent of his personal wealth to charity.<ref>{{cite news|title=I have given 25% of my wealth to charity, Wipro chairman Azim Premji says |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-04-19/india/38673015_1_azim-premji-foundation-giving-pledge-wipro-shares |accessdate=19 April 2013 |newspaper=The Times of India |date=19 April 2013 |agency=PTI |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130419183337/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/I-have-given-25-of-my-wealth-to-charity-Wipro-chairman-Azim-Premji-says/articleshow/19633650.cms |archivedate=19 April 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2015, he gave away an additional 18% of his stake in [[Wipro]], taking his total contribution so far to 39%.<ref>{{cite news |title=Azim Premji gives half of his stake in Wipro for charity|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/it-czar-azim-premji-gives-half-of-his-stake-in-wipro-for-charity/article7399577.ece |date=9 July 2015 | work=[[The Hindu]] |accessdate=9 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Wipro's Azim Premji gives 18% of his stake in company for charity|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/business-news/philanthropist-aziz-premji-gifts-18-more-wipro-stake-to-charity/article1-1367284.aspx |date=9 July 2015 | work=[[Hindustan Times]] |accessdate=9 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of billionaires]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Azim Premji}}\n* [http://www.wipro.com/about-Wipro/Wipro-leadership-team/Azim-H-Premji.aspx Profile] at [[Wipro]]\n* {{Charlie Rose view|651}}\n* {{Worldcat id|lccn-no2003-128963}}\n* [https://www.forbes.com/profile/azim-premji Profile] at [[Forbes]]\n* {{Cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,2066367_2066369_2066101,00.html|title=Azim Premji|first=Bill|last=Gates|date=21 April 2011|accessdate=27 October 2007|work=Time}}\n* {{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2006/aug/27/theobserver.observerbusiness3?INTCMP=SRCH|title=The story of Bangalore Bill|first=David|last=Smith|date=27 August 2006|accessdate=9 August 2011|work=The Guardian }}\n\n{{Padma Vibhushan Awards}}\n{{PadmaBhushanAwardRecipients 2000\u201309}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Premji, Azim}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in software]]\n[[Category:Giving Pledgers]]\n[[Category:21st-century philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Gujarati people]]\n[[Category:Indian billionaires]]\n[[Category:Indian Ismailis]]\n[[Category:Indian company founders]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Bangalore]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Padma Bhushan in trade and industry]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Padma Vibhushan in trade & industry]]\n[[Category:Stanford University alumni]]\n[[Category:Wesleyan University people]]\n[[Category:Wipro]]\n[[Category:Indian philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Founders of Indian schools and colleges]]\n[[Category:Indian industrialists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Kutchi people]]\n[[Category:People from Kutch district]]\n", "name_user": "Suhail hidaya", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added his recognition as one of the most influential 500 Muslims", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Azim_Premji"}
{"title_page": "Connie Douglas Reeves", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Connie Douglas Reeves\n| birth_date =  September 26, 1901 \n| birth_place = [[Eagle Pass, Texas]]\n| death_date = August 17, 2003\n| death_place = [[San Antonio, Texas]]\n| nationality = \n| spouse = \n| children = \n| occupation = \n| movement = \n| party = \n| monuments =\n| religion = \n| influences = \n| influenced =\n| footnotes =\n}}\n'''Connie Douglas Reeves''' (September 26, 1901 \u2013 August 17, 2003) was believed to be America's oldest cowgirl.<ref name=NYT>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/08/25/us/connie-reeves-a-cowgirl-until-the-end-dies-at-101.html | title=Connie Reeves, a Cowgirl Until the End, Dies at 101 | publisher=New York Times| last=Martin | first=Douglas | date=August 25, 2003 | accessdate=May 8, 2017}}</ref> She was the oldest member of the [[National Cowgirl Museum and Hall of Fame]], and one of the first women to study law at a [[University of Texas School of Law]].  One of Reeves most notable quotes was \"Always saddle your own horse\", which [[Liz Smith (journalist)|Liz Smith]] once suggested in her gossip column was \"not a bad motto, even if you are just getting into your Mercedes.\"<ref name=NYT/> In 1998, the [[National Cowboy and Western Heritage Museum]] awarded Reeves the [[Chester A. Reynolds Memorial Award]] for her contributions to the [[Western (genre)|Western]] way of life. She was one of only two women to have earned the award;<ref name=NYT/> the other being [[Mollie Taylor Stevenson Jr.]], founder of the American Cowboy Museum.<ref name=NCMHOF>{{cite web|url=http://www.cowgirl.net/portfolios/mollie-taylor-stevenson-jr/ | title=Mollie Taylor Stevenson, Jr. 2001 Cowgirl Honoree | publisher=Cowgirl Museum & Hall of Fame | accessdate=May 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Early history==\nReeves was born in [[Eagle Pass, Texas]] to William and Ada (Wallace) Douglas.<ref name=KDTObit>{{cite web|url=http://dailytimes.com/obituaries/article_4bb4f09a-791d-5f8c-a70c-2abed0e5368e.html | title=Connie Reeves |publisher=dailytimes.com|date=August 19, 2003|accessdate=May 8, 2017}}</ref> She received her undergraduate degree in speech from [[Texas Woman's University]]. She enrolled in the [[University of Texas School of Law]] in [[Austin, Texas|Austin]], but was forced to withdraw and get a job to help her family during the hard economic times of the [[Great Depression]].  Reeves taught at Thomas Jefferson High School in [[San Antonio]], where she started the \"Lassos\", the first girl\u2019s drill team or pep squad which is still active.<ref name=KDTObit/><ref name=MYSA>{{cite web|url=http://www.mysanantonio.com/news/local_news/article/Jefferson-High-Lassos-were-America-s-sweethearts-4397661.php|title=Jefferson's Lassos Dance Team is Tied to a Proud School History|publisher=Hearst|last=Arias|first=Stefanie|date=April 2, 2013|accessdate=May 8, 2017}}</ref> She also worked part-time as a riding instructor at a local stable.  She grew up around horses and was quoted as saying that she sat on a horse before she could sit up by herself.<ref name=LAT>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2002-sep-22-adna-cowgirl-story.html|title=Cowgirl Won't Be Cowed by Aging|publisher=Los Angeles Times|last=Hastings|first=Deborah|date=22 September 2002|access-date=14 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1936, she joined the equestrian program at Camp Waldemar in [[Hunt, Texas|Hunt]] where she taught horseback riding to girls for 67 years.<ref name=NYT/>  It is estimated that she taught 30,000 girls how to ride at the camp.<ref name=TxH>{{cite news|last=Sullivan|first=Caitlin|title=A Saddle Story|url=http://texashighways.com/people/item/6382-speaking-of-texas-a-saddle-story-connie-douglas-reeves|accessdate=25 September 2014|magazine=[[Texas Highways]]|date=November 2008|page=11}}</ref><ref name=KDT>{{cite web|url=http://dailytimes.com/news/article_14ccbcdf-e87f-562f-9bda-7807faff5334.html | title=Reeves Injured In Riding Accident | last=Raymond | first=Jeff| date=August 7, 2003 |accessdate=May 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\nReeves met her husband Jack at the camp and the couple married in 1942. They also managed {{convert|10000|acre|km2|sigfig=2}} of ranch land owned by former [[President Lyndon B. Johnson]] where they raised [[sheep]] and [[cattle]] for more than forty years. Jack Reeves died in 1985.<ref name=NYT/>\n\n==Recognition==\n\nShe was elected to the Cowgirl Hall of Fame in 1997, and rode in the parade to honor the Hall when it moved to new headquarters in [[Fort Worth, Texas|Fort Worth]] in 2002. She was over 100 years old at the time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cowgirl.net/portfolios/connie-douglas-reeves/|title=Connie Douglas Reeves - Cowgirl Hall of Fame & Museum|work=Cowgirl Hall of Fame & Museum|access-date=2017-04-19|language=en-US}}</ref> She was inducted into the Hall of Great Westerners at the National Cowboy & Western Heritage Museum, Oklahoma City, in 1998.\n\n==Death==\nOn August 5, 2003, Reeves was riding her favorite horse Dr Pepper, a spirited 28-year-old paint.  According to a report by camp director, Meg Clark, the horse threw Reeves over its head. She suffered a broken neck from the fall, but was not paralyzed.<ref name=KDT/> The Associated Press reported that she died of cardiac arrest.  Reeves had suffered several injuries over the past few years of her life, including a fractured thigh that resulted from a kick by the same horse.<ref>Duryea, Bill. [http://www.sptimes.com/2003/09/07/Floridian/A_cowgirl_s_final_ride.shtml \"A cowgirl's final ride,\" ''St. Petersburg Times''.] Retrieved Nov. 2, 2008.</ref>\n\nHer autobiography, ''I Married a Cowboy: Half Century with Girls & Horses at Camp Waldemar'', was published in 1995. Her motto was, \"Always saddle your own horse.\"\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.cowgirl.net/portfolios/connie-douglas-reeves/ Reeves at the Cowgirl Hall of Fame]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Reeves, Connie Douglas}}\n[[Category:1901 births]]\n[[Category:2003 deaths]]\n[[Category:American centenarians]]\n[[Category:Texas Woman's University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Texas School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Cowgirl Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:People from Eagle Pass, Texas]]\n[[Category:Women centenarians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Connie Douglas Reeves\n| birth_date =  September 26, 1901 \n| birth_place = [[Eagle Pass, Texas]]\n| death_date = August 17, 2003\n| death_place = [[San Antonio, Texas]]\n| nationality = \n| spouse = \n| children = \n| occupation = \n| movement = \n| party = \n| monuments =\n| religion = \n| influences = \n| influenced =\n| footnotes =\n}}\n'''Connie Douglas Reeves''' (September 26, 1901 \u2013 August 17, 2003) was believed to be America's oldest cowgirl.<ref name=NYT>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/08/25/us/connie-reeves-a-cowgirl-until-the-end-dies-at-101.html | title=Connie Reeves, a Cowgirl Until the End, Dies at 101 | publisher=New York Times| last=Martin | first=Douglas | date=August 25, 2003 | accessdate=May 8, 2017}}</ref> She was the oldest member of the [[National Cowgirl Museum and Hall of Fame]], and one of the first women to study law at a [[University of Texas School of Law]].  One of Reeves most notable quotes was \"Always saddle your own horse\", which [[Liz Smith (journalist)|Liz Smith]] once suggested in her gossip column was \"not a bad motto, even if you are just getting into your Mercedes.\"<ref name=NYT/> In 1998, the [[National Cowboy and Western Heritage Museum]] awarded Reeves the [[Chester A. Reynolds Memorial Award]] for her contributions to the [[Western (genre)|Western]] way of life. She was one of only two women to have earned the award;<ref name=NYT/> the other being [[Mollie Taylor Stevenson Jr.]], founder of the American Cowboy Museum.<ref name=NCMHOF>{{cite web|url=http://www.cowgirl.net/portfolios/mollie-taylor-stevenson-jr/ | title=Mollie Taylor Stevenson, Jr. 2001 Cowgirl Honoree | publisher=Cowgirl Museum & Hall of Fame | accessdate=May 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Early history==\nReeves was born in [[Eagle Pass, Texas]] to William and Ada (Wallace) Douglas.<ref name=KDTObit>{{cite web|url=http://dailytimes.com/obituaries/article_4bb4f09a-791d-5f8c-a70c-2abed0e5368e.html | title=Connie Reeves |publisher=dailytimes.com|date=August 19, 2003|accessdate=May 8, 2017}}</ref> She received her undergraduate degree in speech from [[Texas Woman's University]]. She enrolled in the [[University of Texas School of Law]] in [[Austin, Texas|Austin]], but was forced to withdraw and get a job to help her family during the hard economic times of the [[Great Depression]].  Reeves taught at Thomas Jefferson High School in [[San Antonio]], where she started the \"Lassos\", the first girl\u2019s drill team or pep squad which is still active.<ref name=KDTObit/><ref name=MYSA>{{cite web|url=http://www.mysanantonio.com/news/local_news/article/Jefferson-High-Lassos-were-America-s-sweethearts-4397661.php|title=Jefferson's Lassos Dance Team is Tied to a Proud School History|publisher=Hearst|last=Arias|first=Stefanie|date=April 2, 2013|accessdate=May 8, 2017}}</ref> She also worked part-time as a riding instructor at a local stable.  She grew up around horses and was quoted as saying that she sat on a horse before she could sit up by herself.<ref name=LAT>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2002-sep-22-adna-cowgirl-story.html|title=Cowgirl Won't Be Cowed by Aging|publisher=Los Angeles Times|last=Hastings|first=Deborah|date=22 September 2002|access-date=14 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1936, she joined the equestrian program at Camp Waldemar in [[Hunt, Texas|Hunt]] where she taught horseback riding to girls for 67 years.<ref name=NYT/>  It is estimated that she taught 30,000 girls how to ride at the camp.<ref name=TxH>{{cite news|last=Sullivan|first=Caitlin|title=A Saddle Story|url=http://texashighways.com/people/item/6382-speaking-of-texas-a-saddle-story-connie-douglas-reeves|accessdate=25 September 2014|magazine=[[Texas Highways]]|date=November 2008|page=11}}</ref><ref name=KDT>{{cite web|url=http://dailytimes.com/news/article_14ccbcdf-e87f-562f-9bda-7807faff5334.html | title=Reeves Injured In Riding Accident | last=Raymond | first=Jeff| date=August 7, 2003 |accessdate=May 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\nReeves met her husband Jack at the camp and the couple married in 1942. They also managed {{convert|10000|acre|km2|sigfig=2}} of ranch land owned by former [[President Lyndon B. Johnson]] where they raised [[sheep]] and [[cattle]] for more than forty years. Jack Reeves died in 1985.<ref name=NYT/>\n\n==Recognition==\n\nShe was elected to the Cowgirl Hall of Fame in 1997, and rode in the parade to honor the Hall when it moved to new headquarters in [[Fort Worth, Texas|Fort Worth]] in 2002. She was over 100 years old at the time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cowgirl.net/portfolios/connie-douglas-reeves/|title=Connie Douglas Reeves - Cowgirl Hall of Fame & Museum|work=Cowgirl Hall of Fame & Museum|access-date=2017-04-19|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nOn August 5, 2003, Reeves was riding her favorite horse Dr Pepper, a spirited 28-year-old paint.  According to a report by camp director, Meg Clark, the horse threw Reeves over its head. She suffered a broken neck from the fall, but was not paralyzed.<ref name=KDT/> The Associated Press reported that she died of cardiac arrest.  Reeves had suffered several injuries over the past few years of her life, including a fractured thigh that resulted from a kick by the same horse.<ref>Duryea, Bill. [http://www.sptimes.com/2003/09/07/Floridian/A_cowgirl_s_final_ride.shtml \"A cowgirl's final ride,\" ''St. Petersburg Times''.] Retrieved Nov. 2, 2008.</ref>\n\nHer autobiography, ''I Married a Cowboy: Half Century with Girls & Horses at Camp Waldemar'', was published in 1995. Her motto was, \"Always saddle your own horse.\"\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.cowgirl.net/portfolios/connie-douglas-reeves/ Reeves at the Cowgirl Hall of Fame]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Reeves, Connie Douglas}}\n[[Category:1901 births]]\n[[Category:2003 deaths]]\n[[Category:American centenarians]]\n[[Category:Texas Woman's University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Texas School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Cowgirl Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:People from Eagle Pass, Texas]]\n[[Category:Women centenarians]]\n", "name_user": "Mrgrauer", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRecognition:Addition to her recognition section.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Connie_Douglas_Reeves"}
{"title_page": "Vijayta Pandit", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2018}}\n{{BLP sources|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Vijayta Pandit\n| image              = VijaytaPandit.jpg\n| imagesize          = \n| caption            = Vijayta Pandit in January 2013\n| yearsactive        = singing: 1977\u2013present<br>acting: 1981\u20131990\n| birth_place        = [[Mumbai]], Maharashtra, India\n| occupation         = Actress, singer\n| birth_name         = Vijayta Pratap Narayan Pandit\n| spouse             = [[Aadesh Shrivastava]] (m. 1990-2015)\n| children           = [[Avitesh Shrivastava]] , Anivesh Shrivastava\n}}\n'''Vijayta Pandit''' is an Indian film actress and playback singer, most famous for her first film ''[[Love Story (1981 film)|Love Story]]'' (1981).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freepressjournal.in/cmcm/bollywoods-forgotten-stars-10-interesting-facts-about-love-story-fame-kumar-gaurav|title=Bollywood\u2019s Forgotten Stars: 10 Interesting facts about \u2018Love Story\u2019 fame Kumar Gaurav|website=Free Press Journal|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and background==\nVijayta comes from a musical family originating from Pili Mandori Village in [[Hisar District|Hissar]] district of [[Haryana]] state. [[Pandit Jasraj]] is her uncle. Her older sister is [[Sulakshana Pandit]], and like her, is an actress and playback singer. Her brothers are music directors [[Jatin Pandit]] and [[Lalit Pandit]], better known as [[Jatin-Lalit]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.idiva.com/entertainment/bollywood/vijeta-pandit-life-has-become-one-big-tragedy/23601|title=Vijeta Pandit: Life Has Become One Big Tragedy {{!}} Entertainment|date=2013-08-15|website=iDiva|language=en-IN|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[Rajendra Kumar]] cast her alongside his son [[Kumar Gaurav]] in ''[[Love Story (1981 film)|Love Story]]'' (1981), which became a \"blockbuster\" at the box office.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat%3D187%26catName%3DMTk4MQ%3D%3D |title=Archived copy |accessdate=27 January 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005055546/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=187&catName=MTk4MQ== |archivedate=5 October 2013 }}</ref> She and Gaurav played star-crossed lovers, and they also developed a relationship off-screen. After the film became a hit, she turned down film offers wanting to be with Gaurav. But the relationship ended, due to family tensions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.screenindia.com/old/20020426/fcover.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081022114050/http://www.screenindia.com/old/20020426/fcover.html |archivedate=22 October 2008 | title=Hits and misses | publisher=Screen | accessdate=2 July 2018 }}</ref> Vijayta went back to films and had another hit ''[[Mohabbat (1985 film)|Mohabbat]]'' (1985).\n\nShe was also briefly married to film director [[Sameer Malkan]] who directed her in the flop ''Car Thief'' (1986). After a few more films, she quit acting and concentrated on playback singing. Her husband, composer [[Aadesh Shrivastava]] has produced a pop album titled ''Propose \u2013 Pyaar ka Izhaar'' which marks Vijayta's debut as a pop singer. Actress [[Madhuri Dixit]] launched the album for the press in February 2007.\n\nSome films wherein Vijayta played the lead are ''[[Jeete Hain Shaan Se]]'' (1986), ''[[Deewana Tere Naam Ka]]'' (1987), ''[[Zalzala (1988 film)|Zalzala]]'' (1988), ''[[Pyar Ka Toofan]]'' (1990). She also sang for films like ''[[Jo Jeeta Wohi Sikandar]]'' (1992), ''[[Kabhi Haan Kabhi Naa]]'' (1993), ''[[Saazish (1998 film)|Saazish]]'' (1998), ''[[Dev (2004 film)|Dev]]'' (2004) and ''[[Chingari (2005 film)|Chingari]]'' (2005).<ref>[http://www.musicindiaonline.com/n/i/top_stories/2120 Madhuri launches Vijayta Pandit's debut pop album \u2013 Music India OnLine<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070223092914/http://www.musicindiaonline.com/n/i/top_stories/2120 |date=23 February 2007 }}</ref>\n\nApart from Hindi films, she has also starred in the blockbuster Bengali film ''[[Amar Sangi]]'' (1987) along with [[Prosenjit Chatterjee|Prasenjit]] directed by [[Sujit Guha]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=0659266}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pandit, Vijayta}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Actresses in Hindi cinema]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Mumbai]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2018}}\n{{BLP sources|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Vijayta Pandit\n| image              = VijaytaPandit.jpg\n| imagesize          = \n| caption            = Vijayta Pandit in January 2013\n| yearsactive        = singing: 1977\u2013present<br>acting: 1981\u20131990\n| birth_place        = [[Mumbai]], Maharashtra, India\n| occupation         = Actress, singer\n| birth_name         = Vijayta Pratap Narayan Pandit\n| spouse             = [[Aadesh Shrivastava]] (m. 1990-2015)\n| children           = Avitesh Shrivastava, Anivesh Shrivastava\n}}\n'''Vijayta Pandit''' is an Indian film actress and playback singer, most famous for her first film ''[[Love Story (1981 film)|Love Story]]'' (1981).\n\n==Early life and background==\nVijayta comes from a musical family originating from Pili Mandori Village in [[Hisar District|Hissar]] district of [[Haryana]] state. [[Pandit Jasraj]] is her uncle. Her older sister is [[Sulakshana Pandit]], and like her, is an actress and playback singer. Her brothers are music directors [[Jatin Pandit]] and [[Lalit Pandit]], better known as [[Jatin-Lalit]].\n\n==Career==\n[[Rajendra Kumar]] cast her alongside his son [[Kumar Gaurav]] in ''[[Love Story (1981 film)|Love Story]]'' (1981), which became a \"blockbuster\" at the box office.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat%3D187%26catName%3DMTk4MQ%3D%3D |title=Archived copy |accessdate=27 January 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005055546/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=187&catName=MTk4MQ== |archivedate=5 October 2013 }}</ref> She and Gaurav played star-crossed lovers, and they also developed a relationship off-screen. After the film became a hit, she turned down film offers wanting to be with Gaurav. But the relationship ended, due to family tensions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.screenindia.com/old/20020426/fcover.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081022114050/http://www.screenindia.com/old/20020426/fcover.html |archivedate=22 October 2008 | title=Hits and misses | publisher=Screen | accessdate=2 July 2018 }}</ref> Vijayta went back to films and had another hit ''[[Mohabbat (1985 film)|Mohabbat]]'' (1985).\n\nShe was also briefly married to film director [[Sameer Malkan]] who directed her in the flop ''Car Thief'' (1986). After a few more films, she quit acting and concentrated on playback singing. Her husband, composer [[Aadesh Shrivastava]] has produced a pop album titled ''Propose \u2013 Pyaar ka Izhaar'' which marks Vijayta's debut as a pop singer. Actress [[Madhuri Dixit]] launched the album for the press in February 2007.\n\nSome films wherein Vijayta played the lead are ''[[Jeete Hain Shaan Se]]'' (1986), ''[[Deewana Tere Naam Ka]]'' (1987), ''[[Zalzala (1988 film)|Zalzala]]'' (1988), ''[[Pyar Ka Toofan]]'' (1990). She also sang for films like ''[[Jo Jeeta Wohi Sikandar]]'' (1992), ''[[Kabhi Haan Kabhi Naa]]'' (1993), ''[[Saazish (1998 film)|Saazish]]'' (1998), ''[[Dev (2004 film)|Dev]]'' (2004) and ''[[Chingari (2005 film)|Chingari]]'' (2005).<ref>[http://www.musicindiaonline.com/n/i/top_stories/2120 Madhuri launches Vijayta Pandit's debut pop album \u2013 Music India OnLine<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070223092914/http://www.musicindiaonline.com/n/i/top_stories/2120 |date=23 February 2007 }}</ref>\n\nApart from Hindi films, she has also starred in the blockbuster Bengali film ''[[Amar Sangi]]'' (1987) along with [[Prosenjit Chatterjee|Prasenjit]] directed by [[Sujit Guha]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=0659266}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pandit, Vijayta}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Actresses in Hindi cinema]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Mumbai]]\n", "name_user": "Anish1121", "label": "safe", "comment": "reference added", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vijayta_Pandit"}
{"title_page": "Mohammad S. Abdeli", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|{{notability|1=Sport|date=April 2020}}{{context|date=April 2020}}{{grammar|date=April 2020}}}}\n\n{{short description|Saudi Arabian footballer}}\n'''Mohammed bin Saad al-Abdali''' (died 7 February 2020) was a Saudi football player who played centre attack. His career spanned nearly 15 years, during which he scored more than 300 goals across friendly and official matches. He is the second best striker in the history of Al-Nassr Football club after [[Majed Abdullah]], and the top scorer for the first Saudi league championship. He was born in the city of [[Ta'if]].<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0627\u0644\u062f\u0648\u0631\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0639\u0648\u062f\u064a \u0642\u0628\u0644 \u0639\u0627\u0645\u0647 \u0627\u064438: \u0627\u0644\u0646\u0635\u0631 \u0623\u0648\u0644 \u0628\u0637\u0644 \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0647\u0644\u0627\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0643\u062b\u0631 \u0641\u0648\u0632\u0627\u064b \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0628\u062f\u0644\u064a \u0623\u0648\u0644 \u0647\u062f\u0627\u0641 \u0648\u0627\u0644\u062d\u0645\u062f\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0633\u0631\u0639 |url=https://www.sauress.com/sportksa/22813 |website=\u0633\u0639\u0648\u0631\u0633 |accessdate=5 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==His Career With Al-Nassr==\n\nAl-Abdali's talent appeared as an accomplished striker. He found the opportunity to showcase his talent at the first team level despite his young age. Only four days into being on the team, Mohammed Saad Al-Abdali scored two goals and made the third goal for his fellow late striker Ahmed Al-Denini. Mohammed Saad al-Abdali is the second-highest scorer in the Riyadh Derby, and scored 18 goals against Al Hilal second  to Majed Abdullah, who scored 21 goals.\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Abdeli, Mohammad}}\n[[Category:People from Ta\u2019if]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Al-Nassr FC players]]\n[[Category:Saudi Professional League players]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Place of death missing]]\n[[Category:Saudi Arabian footballers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|{{notability|1=Sport|date=April 2020}}{{context|date=April 2020}}{{grammar|date=April 2020}}}}\n\n{{short description|Saudi Arabian footballer}}\n'''Mohammed bin Saad al-Abdali''' (died 7 February 2020) was a Saudi football player who played centre attack. His career spanned nearly 15 years, during which he scored more than 300 official and friendly goals. He is the second best striker in the history of Al-Nassr club after [[Majed Abdullah]], and the top scorer for the first Saudi league championship. He was born in the city of [[Ta'if]].<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0627\u0644\u062f\u0648\u0631\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0639\u0648\u062f\u064a \u0642\u0628\u0644 \u0639\u0627\u0645\u0647 \u0627\u064438: \u0627\u0644\u0646\u0635\u0631 \u0623\u0648\u0644 \u0628\u0637\u0644 \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0647\u0644\u0627\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0643\u062b\u0631 \u0641\u0648\u0632\u0627\u064b \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0628\u062f\u0644\u064a \u0623\u0648\u0644 \u0647\u062f\u0627\u0641 \u0648\u0627\u0644\u062d\u0645\u062f\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0633\u0631\u0639 |url=https://www.sauress.com/sportksa/22813 |website=\u0633\u0639\u0648\u0631\u0633 |accessdate=5 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==His Career With Al-Nassr==\n\nAl-Abdali's talent appeared as an accomplished striker. He found the opportunity to showcase his talent at the first team level despite his young age. Only four days into being on the team, Mohammed Saad Al-Abdali scored two goals and made the third goal for his fellow late striker Ahmed Al-Denini. Mohammed Saad al-Abdali is the second-highest scorer in the Riyadh Derby, and scored 18 goals against Al Hilal second  to Majed Abdullah, who scored 21 goals.\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Abdeli, Mohammad}}\n[[Category:People from Ta\u2019if]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Al-Nassr FC players]]\n[[Category:Saudi Professional League players]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Place of death missing]]\n[[Category:Saudi Arabian footballers]]\n", "name_user": "Ptsocial", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mohammad_S._Abdeli"}
{"title_page": "Equilateral triangle", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Equilateral}}\n{{Infobox polygon\n| name      = Equilateral triangle\n| image     = Triangle.Equilateral.svg\n| type      = [[Regular polygon]]\n| edges     = 3\n| schl\u00e4fli  = {3}\n| coxeter   = {{CDD|node_1|3|node}}\n| symmetry  = [[dihedral symmetry|D<sub>3</sub>]]\n| area      = <math>\\tfrac{\\sqrt{3}}{4} a^2</math>\n| angle     = 60\u00b0}}\nIn [[geometry]], an '''equilateral triangle''' is a [[triangle]] in which all three sides are equal. In the familiar [[Euclidean geometry]], an equilateral triangle is also [[equiangular polygon|equiangular]]; that is, all three internal [[angle]]s are also [[congruence (geometry)|congruent]] to each other and are each 60\u00b0. It is also a [[regular polygon]], so it is also referred to as a '''regular triangle'''.\n\n==Principal properties==\n[[File:Equilateral-triangle-heights.svg|300px|thumb|An equilateral triangle. It has equal sides (<math>a = b = c</math>), equal angles (<math>\\alpha = \\beta =\\gamma</math>), and equal altitudes (<math>h_a = h_b = h_c</math>).]]\n<!--Please do not change the formulas, because they are correct. Check your work if you do.-->\nDenoting the common length of the sides of the equilateral triangle as <math>a</math>, we can determine using the [[Pythagorean theorem]] that:\n*The area is <math>A=\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{4} a^2</math>,\n*The perimeter is <math>p=3a\\,\\!</math>\n*The radius of the [[circumscribed circle]] is <math>R = \\frac{a}{\\sqrt{3}}</math>\n*The radius of the [[incircle and excircles of a triangle|inscribed circle]] is <math>r=\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{6} a</math> or <math> r=\\frac{R}{2}</math>\n*The geometric center of the triangle is the center of the circumscribed and inscribed circles\n*The [[altitude (triangle)|altitude]] (height) from any side is <math>h=\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2} a</math>\n\nDenoting the radius of the circumscribed circle as ''R'', we can determine using [[trigonometry]] that:\n*The area of the triangle is <math>\\mathrm{A}=\\frac{3\\sqrt{3}}{4}R^2\n</math>\nMany of these quantities have simple relationships to the altitude (\"h\") of each vertex from the opposite side:\n*The area is <math>A=\\frac{h^2}{\\sqrt{3}}</math>\n*The height of the center from each side, or [[apothem]], is <math>\\frac{h}{3} </math>\n*The radius of the circle circumscribing the three vertices is <math>R=\\frac{2h}{3} </math>\n*The radius of the inscribed circle is <math>r=\\frac{h}{3}</math>\n\nIn an equilateral triangle, the altitudes, the angle bisectors, the perpendicular bisectors, and the medians to each side coincide.\n\n==Characterizations==\n<!--did you know that triangles wasn't considered geometry? Please do not remove this section, see the Talk page for an explanation of the difference between properties and characterizations-->\nA triangle ''ABC'' that has the sides ''a'', ''b'', ''c'', [[semiperimeter]] ''s'', [[area]] ''T'', [[incircle and excircles of a triangle#Relation to area of the triangle|exradii]] ''r<sub>a</sub>'', ''r<sub>b</sub>'', ''r<sub>c</sub>'' (tangent to ''a'', ''b'', ''c'' respectively), and where ''R'' and ''r'' are the radii of the [[circumscribed circle#Triangles|circumcircle]] and [[incircle and excircles of a triangle|incircle]] respectively, is equilateral [[if and only if]] any one of the statements in the following nine categories is true. Thus these are properties that are unique to equilateral triangles, and knowing that any one of them is true directly implies that we have an equilateral triangle.\n\n===Sides===\n*<math>\\displaystyle a=b=c</math>\n*<math>\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{a}+\\frac{1}{b}+\\frac{1}{c}=\\frac{\\sqrt{25Rr-2r^2}}{4Rr}</math><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Bencze|first1=Mih\u00e1ly|last2=Wu|first2=Hui-Hua|last3=Wu|first3=Shan-He|title=An equivalent form of fundamental triangle inequality and its applications|journal=Research Group in Mathematical Inequalities and Applications|date=2008|volume=11|issue=1|url=http://rgmia.org/papers/v11n1/equivalent.pdf}}</ref>\n\n===Semiperimeter===\n*<math>\\displaystyle s=2R+(3\\sqrt{3}-4)r\\quad\\text{(Blundon)}</math><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Dospinescu|first1=G.|last2=Lascu|first2=M.|last3=Pohoata|first3=C.|last4=Letiva|first4=M.|title=An elementary proof of Blundon's inequality|journal=Journal of inequalities in pure and applied mathematics|date=2008|volume=9|issue=4|url=http://www.emis.de/journals/JIPAM/images/220_08_JIPAM/220_08_www.pdf}}</ref>\n*<math>\\displaystyle s^2=3r^2+12Rr</math><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Blundon|first1=W. J.|title=On Certain Polynomials Associated with the Triangle|journal=Mathematics Magazine|date=1963|volume=36|issue=4|pages=247\u2013248|doi=10.2307/2687913}}</ref>\n*<math>\\displaystyle s^2=3\\sqrt{3}T</math><ref name=Alsina>{{cite book|last1=Alsina|first1=Claudi|last2=Nelsen|first2=Roger B.|title=''When less is more. Visualizing basic inequalities|date=2009|publisher=Mathematical Association of America|pages=71, 155}}</ref>\n*<math>\\displaystyle s=3\\sqrt{3}r</math>\n*<math>\\displaystyle s=\\frac{3\\sqrt{3}}{2}R</math>\n\n===Angles===\n*<math>\\displaystyle A=B=C=60^\\circ</math>\n*<math>\\displaystyle \\cos{A}+\\cos{B}+\\cos{C}=\\frac{3}{2}</math>\n*<math>\\displaystyle \\sin{\\frac{A}{2}}\\sin{\\frac{B}{2}}\\sin{\\frac{C}{2}}=\\frac{1}{8}</math><ref name=Cosmin/>\n\n===Area===\n*<math>\\displaystyle T=\\frac{a^2+b^2+c^2}{4\\sqrt{3}}\\quad</math> ([[Weitzenb\u00f6ck's inequality|Weitzenb\u00f6ck]])<ref>{{cite web|last1=McLeman |first1=Cam |last2=Ismail |first2=Andrei |title=Weizenbock's inequality |url=http://planetmath.org/encyclopedia/WeizenbocksInequality.html |website=PlanetMath |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120218055252/http://planetmath.org/encyclopedia/WeizenbocksInequality.html |archivedate=2012-02-18 }}</ref>\n*<math>\\displaystyle T=\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{4}(abc)^{^{\\frac{2}{3}}}</math><ref name=Alsina/>\n\n===Circumradius, inradius, and exradii===\n*<math>\\displaystyle R=2r\\quad\\text{(Chapple-Euler)}</math><ref name=Andreescu/>\n*<math>\\displaystyle 9R^2=a^2+b^2+c^2</math><ref name=Andreescu/>\n*<math>\\displaystyle r=\\frac{r_a+r_b+r_c}{9}</math><ref name=Cosmin>{{cite journal|last1=Pohoata|first1=Cosmin|title=A new proof of Euler's inradius - circumradius inequality|journal=Gazeta Matematica Seria B|date=2010|issue=3|pages=121\u2013123|url=http://rms.unibuc.ro/gazeta/gmb/2010/3/articol.pdf}}</ref>\n*<math>\\displaystyle r_a=r_b=r_c</math>\n\n===Equal cevians===\nThree kinds of [[cevian]]s coincide, and are equal, for (and only for) equilateral triangles:<ref>{{cite book|last1=Owen|first1=Byer|last2=Felix|first2=Lazebnik|last3=Deirdre|first3=Smeltzer|title=Methods for Euclidean Geometry|date=2010|publisher=Mathematical Association of America|pages=36, 39}}</ref>\n*The three [[altitude (triangle)|altitude]]s have equal lengths.\n*The three [[median (geometry)|median]]s have equal lengths.\n*The three [[bisection#Angle bisector|angle bisector]]s have equal lengths.\n\n===Coincident triangle centers===\nEvery [[triangle center]] of an equilateral triangle coincides with its [[centroid]], which implies that the equilateral triangle is the only triangle with no [[Euler line]] connecting some of the centers. For some pairs of triangle centers, the fact that they coincide is enough to ensure that the triangle is equilateral. In particular:\n\n*A triangle is equilateral if any two of the [[circumscribed circle|circumcenter]], [[incircle and excircles of a triangle|incenter]], centroid, or [[altitude (triangle)|orthocenter]] coincide.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Yiu|first1=Paul|title=Notes on Euclidean Geometry|url=http://math.fau.edu/Yiu/EuclideanGeometryNotes.pdf|date=1998}}</ref>{{rp|p.37}}\n*It is also equilateral if its circumcenter coincides with the [[Nagel point]], or if its incenter coincides with its [[nine-point circle#Other properties of the nine-point circle|nine-point center]].<ref name=Andreescu>{{cite book|last1=Andreescu|first1=Titu|last2=Andrica|first2=Dorian|title=Complex Numbers from A to...Z|date=2006|publisher=Birkh\u00e4user|pages=70, 113\u2013115}}</ref>\n\n===Six triangles formed by partitioning by the medians===\n\nFor any triangle, the three [[median (geometry)|medians]] partition the triangle into six smaller triangles.\n*A triangle is equilateral if and only if any three of the smaller triangles have either the same perimeter or the same inradius.<ref name=Cerin>{{cite journal|last1=Cerin|first1=Zvonko|title=The vertex-midpoint-centroid triangles|journal=Forum Geometricorum|date=2004|volume=4|pages=97\u2013109|url=http://forumgeom.fau.edu/FG2004volume4/FG200413.pdf}}</ref>{{rp|Theorem 1}}\n*A triangle is equilateral if and only if the circumcenters of any three of the smaller triangles have the same distance from the centroid.<ref name=Cerin/>{{rp|Corollary 7}}\n\n===Points in the plane===\n*A triangle is equilateral if and only if, for ''every'' point ''P'' in the plane, with distances ''p'', ''q'', and ''r'' to the triangle's sides and distances ''x'', ''y'', and ''z'' to its vertices,<ref name=Crux/>{{rp|p.178,#235.4}}\n::<math>4(p^2+q^2+r^2) \\geq x^2+y^2+z^2.</math>\n\n==Notable theorems==\n[[File:Viviani_theorem_visual_proof.svg|thumb|Visual proof of Viviani's theorem\n{|\n|valign=\"top\"|1.||Nearest distances from point P to sides of equilateral triangle ABC are shown.\n|-\n|valign=\"top\"|2.||Lines DE, FG, and HI parallel to AB, BC and CA, respectively, define smaller triangles PHE, PFI and PDG.\n|-\n|valign=\"top\"|3.||As these triangles are equilateral, their altitudes can be rotated to be vertical.\n|-\n|valign=\"top\"|4.||As PGCH is a parallelogram, triangle PHE can be slid up to show that the altitudes sum to that of triangle ABC.\n|} ]]\n[[Morley's trisector theorem]] states that, in any triangle, the three points of intersection of the adjacent [[angle trisection|angle trisectors]] form an equilateral triangle.\n\n[[Napoleon's theorem]] states that, if equilateral triangles are constructed on the sides of any triangle, either all outward, or all inward, the centers of those equilateral triangles themselves form an equilateral triangle.\n\nA version of the [[isoperimetric inequality]] for triangles states that the triangle of greatest [[area]] among all those with a given [[perimeter]] is equilateral.<ref name=Chakerian/>\n\n[[Viviani's theorem]] states that, for any interior point ''P'' in an equilateral triangle with distances ''d'', ''e'', and ''f'' from the sides and altitude ''h'',\n:<math>d+e+f=h,</math>\nindependent of the location of ''P''.<ref name=Posamentier>{{cite book|last1=Posamentier|first1=Alfred S.|last2=Salkind|first2=Charles T.|title=Challenging Problems in Geometry|url=https://archive.org/details/challengingprobl0000posa|url-access=registration|date=1996|publisher=Dover Publ.}}</ref>\n\n[[Pompeiu's theorem]] states that, if ''P'' is an arbitrary point in the plane of an equilateral triangle ''ABC'' but not on its [[circumcircle]], then there exists a triangle with sides of lengths ''PA'', ''PB'', and ''PC''. That is, ''PA'', ''PB'', and ''PC'' satisfy the [[triangle inequality]] that the sum of any two of them is greater than the third. If ''P'' is on the circumcircle then the sum of the two smaller ones equals the longest and the triangle has degenerated into a line, this case is known as [[Van Schooten's theorem]].\n\n==Other properties==\nBy [[Euler's theorem in geometry|Euler's inequality]], the equilateral triangle has the smallest ratio ''R''/''r'' of the circumradius to the inradius of any triangle: specifically, ''R''/''r'' = 2.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Svrtan|first1=Dragutin|last2=Veljan|first2=Darko|title=Non-Euclidean versions of some classical triangle inequalities|journal=Forum Geometricorum|date=2012|volume=12|pages=197\u2013209|url=http://forumgeom.fau.edu/FG2012volume12/FG201217.pdf}}</ref>{{rp|p.198}}\n\nThe triangle of largest area of all those inscribed in a given circle is equilateral; and the triangle of smallest area of all those circumscribed around a given circle is equilateral.<ref>{{cite book|last1=D\u00f6rrie|first1=Heinrich|title=100 Great Problems of Elementary Mathematics|date=1965|publisher=Dover Publ.|pages=379\u2013380}}</ref>\n\nThe ratio of the area of the incircle to the area of an equilateral triangle, <math>\\frac{\\pi}{3\\sqrt{3}}</math>, is larger than that of any non-equilateral triangle.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Minda|first1=D.|last2=Phelps|first2=S.|title=Triangles, ellipses, and cubic polynomials|journal=American Mathematical Monthly|date=2008|volume=115|issue=October|pages=679\u2013689|jstor=27642581|doi=10.1080/00029890.2008.11920581}}</ref>{{rp|Theorem 4.1}}\n\nThe ratio of the area to the square of the perimeter of an equilateral triangle, <math>\\frac{1}{12\\sqrt{3}},</math> is larger than that for any other triangle.<ref name=Chakerian>Chakerian, G. D. \"A Distorted View of Geometry.\" Ch. 7 in ''Mathematical Plums'' (R. Honsberger, editor). Washington, DC: Mathematical Association of America, 1979: 147.</ref>\n\nIf a segment splits an equilateral triangle into two regions with equal perimeters and with areas ''A''<sub>1</sub> and ''A''<sub>2</sub>, then<ref name=Crux>{{cite web|title=Inequalities proposed in \"Crux Mathematicorum\"|url=http://hydra.nat.uni-magdeburg.de/math4u/ineq.pdf}}</ref>{{rp|p.151,#J26}}\n:<math>\\frac{7}{9} \\leq \\frac{A_1}{A_2} \\leq \\frac{9}{7}.</math>\n\nIf a triangle is placed in the [[complex plane]] with complex vertices ''z''<sub>1</sub>, ''z''<sub>2</sub>, and ''z''<sub>3</sub>, then for either non-real cube root <math>\\omega</math> of 1 the triangle is equilateral if and only if<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Dao|first1=Thanh Oai|title=Equilateral triangles and Kiepert perspectors in complex numbers|journal=Forum Geometricorum|date=2015|volume=15|pages=105\u2013114|url=http://forumgeom.fau.edu/FG2015volume15/FG201509.pdf}}</ref>{{rp|Lemma 2}}\n:<math>z_1+\\omega z_2+\\omega^2 z_3 =0.</math>\n\nGiven a point ''P'' in the interior of an equilateral triangle, the ratio of the sum of its distances from the vertices to the sum of its distances from the sides is greater than or equal to 2, equality holding when ''P'' is the centroid. In no other triangle is there a point for which this ratio is as small as 2.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lee|first1=Hojoo|title=Another proof of the Erd\u0151s\u2013Mordell Theorem|journal=Forum Geometricorum|date=2001|volume=1|pages=7\u20138|url=http://forumgeom.fau.edu/FG2001volume1/FG200102.pdf}}</ref> This is the [[Erd\u0151s\u2013Mordell inequality]]; a stronger variant of it is [[Barrow's inequality]], which replaces the perpendicular distances to the sides with the distances from ''P'' to the points where the [[angle bisector]]s of \u2220''APB'', \u2220''BPC'', and \u2220''CPA'' cross the sides (''A'', ''B'', and ''C'' being the vertices).\n\nFor any point ''P'' in the plane, with distances ''p'', ''q'', and ''t'' from the vertices ''A'', ''B'', and ''C'' respectively,<ref>Gardner, Martin, \"Elegant Triangles\", in the book ''Mathematical Circus'', 1979, p. 65.</ref>\n:<math>\\displaystyle 3(p^{4}+q^{4}+t^{4}+a^{4})=(p^{2}+q^{2}+t^{2}+a^{2})^{2}.</math>\n\nFor any point ''P'' in the plane, with distances ''p'', ''q'', and ''t'' from the vertices, <ref>{{citation|first=Mamuka|last=Meskhishvili|title=Cyclic Averages of Regular Polygons|url=https://www.gysu.org/copy-of-contact-us?fbclid=IwAR086p2tvNg3wYJy_agiwGj5gXlntfco6kpNjBurGqZcGeUjjcfxLM31xeo}}</ref>\n:<math>\\displaystyle p^{2}+q^{2}+t^{2}=3(R^{2}+L^{2})</math>\nand\n:<math>\\displaystyle p^{4}+q^{4}+t^{4}=3[(R^{2}+L^{2})^{2}+2R^{2}L^{2}],</math>\nwhere ''R''  is the circumscribed radius and ''L''   is the distance between point ''P''  and the centroid of the equilateral triangle.\n\nFor any point ''P'' on the inscribed circle of an equilateral triangle, with distances ''p'', ''q'', and ''t'' from the vertices,<ref name=De>{{cite journal|last1=De|first1=Prithwijit|title=Curious properties of the circumcircle and incircle of an equilateral triangle|journal=Mathematical Spectrum|date=2008|volume=41|issue=1|pages=32\u201335|url=http://www.appliedprobability.org/data/files/MS%20issues/Vol41_No1.pdf}}</ref>\n:<math>\\displaystyle 4(p^{2}+q^{2}+t^{2})=5a^{2}</math>\nand\n:<math>\\displaystyle 16(p^{4}+q^{4}+t^{4})=11a^{4}.</math>\n\nFor any point ''P'' on the minor arc BC of the circumcircle, with distances ''p'', ''q'', and ''t'' from A, B, and C respectively,<ref name=Posamentier>{{cite book|last1=Posamentier|first1=Alfred S.|last2=Salkind|first2=Charles T.|title=Challenging Problems in Geometry|url=https://archive.org/details/challengingprobl0000posa|url-access=registration|date=1996|publisher=Dover Publ.}}</ref>\n:<math>\\displaystyle p=q+t</math>\nand\n:<math>\\displaystyle q^{2}+qt+t^{2}=a^{2} ;</math>\n\nmoreover, if point D on side BC divides PA into segments PD and DA with DA having length ''z'' and PD having length ''y'', then <ref name=Posamentier/>{{rp|172}}\n:<math>z= \\frac{t^{2}+tq+q^2}{t+q},</math>\n\nwhich also equals <math>\\tfrac{t^{3}-q^{3}}{t^{2}-q^{2}}</math> if ''t'' \u2260 ''q''; and\n:<math>\\frac{1}{q}+\\frac{1}{t}=\\frac{1}{y},</math>\nwhich is the [[optic equation]].\n\nThere are numerous [[list of triangle inequalities|triangle inequalities]] that hold with equality if and only if the triangle is equilateral.\n\nAn equilateral triangle is the most symmetrical triangle, having 3 lines of [[reflection symmetry|reflection]] and [[rotational symmetry]] of order 3 about its center. Its [[symmetry group]] is the [[dihedral group of order 6]] ''D''<sub>3</sub>.\n\nEquilateral triangles are the only triangles whose [[Steiner inellipse]] is a circle (specifically, it is the incircle).\n\nThe integer-sided equilateral triangle is the only [[integer triangle|triangle with integer sides]] and three rational angles as measured in degrees.<ref name=CG>Conway, J. H., and Guy, R. K., \"The only rational triangle\", in ''The Book of Numbers'', 1996, Springer-Verlag, pp. 201 and 228\u2013239.</ref>\n\nThe equilateral triangle is the only acute triangle that is similar to its [[orthic triangle]] (with vertices at the feet of the [[altitude (geometry)|altitudes]]) (the [[heptagonal triangle]] being the only obtuse one).<ref name=BG>Leon Bankoff and Jack Garfunkel, \"The heptagonal triangle\", ''[[Mathematics Magazine]]'' 46 (1), January 1973, 7\u201319.</ref>{{rp|p. 19}}\n\n[[File:Viervlak-frame.jpg|thumb|right|A regular tetrahedron is made of four equilateral triangles.]]\nEquilateral triangles are found in many other geometric constructs. The intersection of circles whose centers are a radius width apart is a pair of equilateral arches, each of which can be inscribed with an equilateral triangle. They form faces of regular and uniform [[polyhedra]]. Three of the five [[Platonic solid]]s are composed of equilateral triangles. In particular, the [[tetrahedron|regular tetrahedron]] has four equilateral triangles for faces and can be considered the three-dimensional analogue of the shape. The plane can be [[Euclidean tilings by convex regular polygons|tiled]] using equilateral triangles giving the [[triangular tiling]].\n\n==Geometric construction==\n\n[[File:Equilateral triangle construction.svg|200px|thumb|right|Construction of equilateral triangle with compass and straightedge]]\n\nAn equilateral triangle is easily constructed using a [[straightedge and compass]], because 3 is a [[Fermat prime]]. Draw a straight line, and place the point of the compass on one end of the line, and swing an arc from that point to the other point of the line segment. Repeat with the other side of the line. Finally, connect the point where the two arcs intersect with each end of the line segment\n\nAn alternative method is to draw a circle with radius ''r'', place the point of the compass on the circle and draw another circle with the same radius. The two circles will intersect in two points. An equilateral triangle can be constructed by taking the two centers of the circles and either of the points of intersection.\n\nIn both methods a by-product is the formation of [[vesica piscis]].\n\nThe proof that the resulting figure is an equilateral triangle is the first proposition in Book I of [[Euclid's Elements|Euclid's ''Elements'']].\n\n[[File:Equilateral_Triangle_Inscribed_in_a_Circle.gif|center]]\n\n==Derivation of area formula==\nThe area formula <math>A = \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{4}a^2</math> in terms of side length ''a'' can be derived directly using the Pythagorean theorem or using trigonometry.\n\n===Using the Pythagorean theorem===\nThe area of a triangle is half of one side ''a'' times the height ''h'' from that side:\n:<math>A = \\frac{1}{2} ah.</math>\n\n[[File:30-60-90.svg|thumb|150px|An equilateral triangle with a side of 2 has a height of {{sqrt|3}} as the sine of 60\u00b0 is {{sqrt|3}}/2.]]\nThe legs of either right triangle formed by an altitude of the equilateral triangle are half of the base ''a'', and the hypotenuse is the side ''a'' of the equilateral triangle. The height of an equilateral triangle can be found using the [[Pythagorean theorem]]\n:<math>\\left(\\frac{a}{2}\\right)^2 + h^2 = a^2</math>\n\nso that\n:<math>h = \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2}a.</math>\n\nSubstituting ''h'' into the area formula (1/2)''ah'' gives the area formula for the equilateral triangle:\n:<math>A = \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{4}a^2.</math>\n\n===Using trigonometry===\nUsing [[trigonometry]], the area of a triangle with any two sides ''a'' and ''b'', and an angle ''C'' between them is\n:<math>A = \\frac{1}{2} ab \\sin C.</math>\n\nEach angle of an equilateral triangle is 60\u00b0, so\n:<math>A = \\frac{1}{2} ab \\sin 60^\\circ.</math>\n\nThe sine of 60\u00b0 is <math>\\tfrac{\\sqrt{3}}{2}</math>. Thus\n:<math>A = \\frac{1}{2} ab \\times \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2} = \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{4}ab = \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{4}a^2</math>\nsince all sides of an equilateral triangle are equal.\n\n==In culture and society==\nEquilateral triangles have frequently appeared in man made constructions:\n*The shape occurs in modern architecture such as the cross-section of the [[Gateway Arch]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Eero Saarinen: Shaping the Future|editor1-first=Eeva-Liisa|editor1-last=Pelkonen|editor2-first=Donald|editor2-last=Albrecht|publisher=Yale University Press|year=2006|isbn=978-0972488129|pages=[https://archive.org/details/eerosaarinenshap0000saar/page/160 160, 224, 226]|url=https://archive.org/details/eerosaarinenshap0000saar/page/160}}</ref>\n*Its applications in flags and heraldry includes the [[flag of Nicaragua]]<ref>{{cite book|title=Culture and Customs of Nicaragua|first1=Steven F.|last1=White|first2=Esthela|last2=Calder\u00f3n|publisher=Greenwood Press|year=2008|page=[https://archive.org/details/culturecustomsof00stev/page/3 3]|isbn=978-0313339943|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/culturecustomsof00stev/page/3}}</ref> and the [[flag of the Philippines]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Historical Dictionary of the Philippines|first=Artemio R.|last=Guillermo|publisher=Scarecrow Press|year=2012|isbn=978-0810872462|page=161|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wmgX9M_yETIC&pg=PA161}}</ref>\n*It is a shape of a variety of [[traffic sign|road signs]], including the [[yield sign]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Riley|first1=Michael W.|last2=Cochran|first2=David J.|last3=Ballard|first3=John L.|date=December 1982|doi=10.1177/001872088202400610|issue=6|journal=Human Factors: The Journal of the Human Factors and Ergonomics Society|pages=737\u2013742|title=An Investigation of Preferred Shapes for Warning Labels|volume=24}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Heronian triangle#Almost-equilateral Heronian triangles|Almost-equilateral Heronian triangle]]\n*[[Isosceles triangle]]\n*[[Ternary plot]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{MathWorld|title=Equilateral Triangle|urlname=EquilateralTriangle}}\n\n{{Polygons}}\n{{Polytopes}}\n\n[[Category:Triangles]]\n[[Category:Triangle geometry]]\n[[Category:Elementary shapes]]\n[[Category:Constructible polygons]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Equilateral}}\n{{Infobox polygon\n| name      = Equilateral triangle\n| image     = Triangle.Equilateral.svg\n| type      = [[Regular polygon]]\n| edges     = 3\n| schl\u00e4fli  = {3}\n| coxeter   = {{CDD|node_1|3|node}}\n| symmetry  = [[dihedral symmetry|D<sub>3</sub>]]\n| area      = <math>\\tfrac{\\sqrt{3}}{4} a^2</math>\n| angle     = 60\u00b0}}\nIn [[geometry]], an '''equilateral triangle''' is a [[triangle]] in which all three sides are equal. In the familiar [[Euclidean geometry]], an equilateral triangle is also [[equiangular polygon|equiangular]]; that is, all three internal [[angle]]s are also [[congruence (geometry)|congruent]] to each other and are each 60\u00b0. It is also a [[regular polygon]], so it is also referred to as a '''regular triangle'''.\n\n==Principal properties==\n[[File:Equilateral-triangle-heights.svg|300px|thumb|An equilateral triangle. It has equal sides (<math>a = b = c</math>), equal angles (<math>\\alpha = \\beta =\\gamma</math>), and equal altitudes (<math>h_a = h_b = h_c</math>).]]\n<!--Please do not change the formulas, because they are correct. Check your work if you do.-->\nDenoting the common length of the sides of the equilateral triangle as <math>a</math>, we can determine using the [[Pythagorean theorem]] that:\n*The area is <math>A=\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{4} a^2</math>,\n*The perimeter is <math>p=3a\\,\\!</math>\n*The radius of the [[circumscribed circle]] is <math>R = \\frac{a}{\\sqrt{3}}</math>\n*The radius of the [[incircle and excircles of a triangle|inscribed circle]] is <math>r=\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{6} a</math> or <math> r=\\frac{R}{2}</math>\n*The geometric center of the triangle is the center of the circumscribed and inscribed circles\n*The [[altitude (triangle)|altitude]] (height) from any side is <math>h=\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2} a</math>\n\nDenoting the radius of the circumscribed circle as ''R'', we can determine using [[trigonometry]] that:\n*The area of the triangle is <math>\\mathrm{A}=\\frac{3\\sqrt{3}}{4}R^2\n</math>\nMany of these quantities have simple relationships to the altitude (\"h\") of each vertex from the opposite side:\n*The area is <math>A=\\frac{h^2}{\\sqrt{3}}</math>\n*The height of the center from each side, or [[apothem]], is <math>\\frac{h}{3} </math>\n*The radius of the circle circumscribing the three vertices is <math>R=\\frac{2h}{3} </math>\n*The radius of the inscribed circle is <math>r=\\frac{h}{3}</math>\n\nIn an equilateral triangle, the altitudes, the angle bisectors, the perpendicular bisectors, and the medians to each side coincide.\n\n==Characterizations==\n<!--Please do not remove this section, see the Talk page for an explanation of the difference between properties and characterizations-->\nA triangle ''ABC'' that has the sides ''a'', ''b'', ''c'', [[semiperimeter]] ''s'', [[area]] ''T'', [[incircle and excircles of a triangle#Relation to area of the triangle|exradii]] ''r<sub>a</sub>'', ''r<sub>b</sub>'', ''r<sub>c</sub>'' (tangent to ''a'', ''b'', ''c'' respectively), and where ''R'' and ''r'' are the radii of the [[circumscribed circle#Triangles|circumcircle]] and [[incircle and excircles of a triangle|incircle]] respectively, is equilateral [[if and only if]] any one of the statements in the following nine categories is true. Thus these are properties that are unique to equilateral triangles, and knowing that any one of them is true directly implies that we have an equilateral triangle.\n\n===Sides===\n*<math>\\displaystyle a=b=c</math>\n*<math>\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{a}+\\frac{1}{b}+\\frac{1}{c}=\\frac{\\sqrt{25Rr-2r^2}}{4Rr}</math><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Bencze|first1=Mih\u00e1ly|last2=Wu|first2=Hui-Hua|last3=Wu|first3=Shan-He|title=An equivalent form of fundamental triangle inequality and its applications|journal=Research Group in Mathematical Inequalities and Applications|date=2008|volume=11|issue=1|url=http://rgmia.org/papers/v11n1/equivalent.pdf}}</ref>\n\n===Semiperimeter===\n*<math>\\displaystyle s=2R+(3\\sqrt{3}-4)r\\quad\\text{(Blundon)}</math><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Dospinescu|first1=G.|last2=Lascu|first2=M.|last3=Pohoata|first3=C.|last4=Letiva|first4=M.|title=An elementary proof of Blundon's inequality|journal=Journal of inequalities in pure and applied mathematics|date=2008|volume=9|issue=4|url=http://www.emis.de/journals/JIPAM/images/220_08_JIPAM/220_08_www.pdf}}</ref>\n*<math>\\displaystyle s^2=3r^2+12Rr</math><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Blundon|first1=W. J.|title=On Certain Polynomials Associated with the Triangle|journal=Mathematics Magazine|date=1963|volume=36|issue=4|pages=247\u2013248|doi=10.2307/2687913}}</ref>\n*<math>\\displaystyle s^2=3\\sqrt{3}T</math><ref name=Alsina>{{cite book|last1=Alsina|first1=Claudi|last2=Nelsen|first2=Roger B.|title=''When less is more. Visualizing basic inequalities|date=2009|publisher=Mathematical Association of America|pages=71, 155}}</ref>\n*<math>\\displaystyle s=3\\sqrt{3}r</math>\n*<math>\\displaystyle s=\\frac{3\\sqrt{3}}{2}R</math>\n\n===Angles===\n*<math>\\displaystyle A=B=C=60^\\circ</math>\n*<math>\\displaystyle \\cos{A}+\\cos{B}+\\cos{C}=\\frac{3}{2}</math>\n*<math>\\displaystyle \\sin{\\frac{A}{2}}\\sin{\\frac{B}{2}}\\sin{\\frac{C}{2}}=\\frac{1}{8}</math><ref name=Cosmin/>\n\n===Area===\n*<math>\\displaystyle T=\\frac{a^2+b^2+c^2}{4\\sqrt{3}}\\quad</math> ([[Weitzenb\u00f6ck's inequality|Weitzenb\u00f6ck]])<ref>{{cite web|last1=McLeman |first1=Cam |last2=Ismail |first2=Andrei |title=Weizenbock's inequality |url=http://planetmath.org/encyclopedia/WeizenbocksInequality.html |website=PlanetMath |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120218055252/http://planetmath.org/encyclopedia/WeizenbocksInequality.html |archivedate=2012-02-18 }}</ref>\n*<math>\\displaystyle T=\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{4}(abc)^{^{\\frac{2}{3}}}</math><ref name=Alsina/>\n\n===Circumradius, inradius, and exradii===\n*<math>\\displaystyle R=2r\\quad\\text{(Chapple-Euler)}</math><ref name=Andreescu/>\n*<math>\\displaystyle 9R^2=a^2+b^2+c^2</math><ref name=Andreescu/>\n*<math>\\displaystyle r=\\frac{r_a+r_b+r_c}{9}</math><ref name=Cosmin>{{cite journal|last1=Pohoata|first1=Cosmin|title=A new proof of Euler's inradius - circumradius inequality|journal=Gazeta Matematica Seria B|date=2010|issue=3|pages=121\u2013123|url=http://rms.unibuc.ro/gazeta/gmb/2010/3/articol.pdf}}</ref>\n*<math>\\displaystyle r_a=r_b=r_c</math>\n\n===Equal cevians===\nThree kinds of [[cevian]]s coincide, and are equal, for (and only for) equilateral triangles:<ref>{{cite book|last1=Owen|first1=Byer|last2=Felix|first2=Lazebnik|last3=Deirdre|first3=Smeltzer|title=Methods for Euclidean Geometry|date=2010|publisher=Mathematical Association of America|pages=36, 39}}</ref>\n*The three [[altitude (triangle)|altitude]]s have equal lengths.\n*The three [[median (geometry)|median]]s have equal lengths.\n*The three [[bisection#Angle bisector|angle bisector]]s have equal lengths.\n\n===Coincident triangle centers===\nEvery [[triangle center]] of an equilateral triangle coincides with its [[centroid]], which implies that the equilateral triangle is the only triangle with no [[Euler line]] connecting some of the centers. For some pairs of triangle centers, the fact that they coincide is enough to ensure that the triangle is equilateral. In particular:\n\n*A triangle is equilateral if any two of the [[circumscribed circle|circumcenter]], [[incircle and excircles of a triangle|incenter]], centroid, or [[altitude (triangle)|orthocenter]] coincide.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Yiu|first1=Paul|title=Notes on Euclidean Geometry|url=http://math.fau.edu/Yiu/EuclideanGeometryNotes.pdf|date=1998}}</ref>{{rp|p.37}}\n*It is also equilateral if its circumcenter coincides with the [[Nagel point]], or if its incenter coincides with its [[nine-point circle#Other properties of the nine-point circle|nine-point center]].<ref name=Andreescu>{{cite book|last1=Andreescu|first1=Titu|last2=Andrica|first2=Dorian|title=Complex Numbers from A to...Z|date=2006|publisher=Birkh\u00e4user|pages=70, 113\u2013115}}</ref>\n\n===Six triangles formed by partitioning by the medians===\n\nFor any triangle, the three [[median (geometry)|medians]] partition the triangle into six smaller triangles.\n*A triangle is equilateral if and only if any three of the smaller triangles have either the same perimeter or the same inradius.<ref name=Cerin>{{cite journal|last1=Cerin|first1=Zvonko|title=The vertex-midpoint-centroid triangles|journal=Forum Geometricorum|date=2004|volume=4|pages=97\u2013109|url=http://forumgeom.fau.edu/FG2004volume4/FG200413.pdf}}</ref>{{rp|Theorem 1}}\n*A triangle is equilateral if and only if the circumcenters of any three of the smaller triangles have the same distance from the centroid.<ref name=Cerin/>{{rp|Corollary 7}}\n\n===Points in the plane===\n*A triangle is equilateral if and only if, for ''every'' point ''P'' in the plane, with distances ''p'', ''q'', and ''r'' to the triangle's sides and distances ''x'', ''y'', and ''z'' to its vertices,<ref name=Crux/>{{rp|p.178,#235.4}}\n::<math>4(p^2+q^2+r^2) \\geq x^2+y^2+z^2.</math>\n\n==Notable theorems==\n[[File:Viviani_theorem_visual_proof.svg|thumb|Visual proof of Viviani's theorem\n{|\n|valign=\"top\"|1.||Nearest distances from point P to sides of equilateral triangle ABC are shown.\n|-\n|valign=\"top\"|2.||Lines DE, FG, and HI parallel to AB, BC and CA, respectively, define smaller triangles PHE, PFI and PDG.\n|-\n|valign=\"top\"|3.||As these triangles are equilateral, their altitudes can be rotated to be vertical.\n|-\n|valign=\"top\"|4.||As PGCH is a parallelogram, triangle PHE can be slid up to show that the altitudes sum to that of triangle ABC.\n|} ]]\n[[Morley's trisector theorem]] states that, in any triangle, the three points of intersection of the adjacent [[angle trisection|angle trisectors]] form an equilateral triangle.\n\n[[Napoleon's theorem]] states that, if equilateral triangles are constructed on the sides of any triangle, either all outward, or all inward, the centers of those equilateral triangles themselves form an equilateral triangle.\n\nA version of the [[isoperimetric inequality]] for triangles states that the triangle of greatest [[area]] among all those with a given [[perimeter]] is equilateral.<ref name=Chakerian/>\n\n[[Viviani's theorem]] states that, for any interior point ''P'' in an equilateral triangle with distances ''d'', ''e'', and ''f'' from the sides and altitude ''h'',\n:<math>d+e+f=h,</math>\nindependent of the location of ''P''.<ref name=Posamentier>{{cite book|last1=Posamentier|first1=Alfred S.|last2=Salkind|first2=Charles T.|title=Challenging Problems in Geometry|url=https://archive.org/details/challengingprobl0000posa|url-access=registration|date=1996|publisher=Dover Publ.}}</ref>\n\n[[Pompeiu's theorem]] states that, if ''P'' is an arbitrary point in the plane of an equilateral triangle ''ABC'' but not on its [[circumcircle]], then there exists a triangle with sides of lengths ''PA'', ''PB'', and ''PC''. That is, ''PA'', ''PB'', and ''PC'' satisfy the [[triangle inequality]] that the sum of any two of them is greater than the third. If ''P'' is on the circumcircle then the sum of the two smaller ones equals the longest and the triangle has degenerated into a line, this case is known as [[Van Schooten's theorem]].\n\n==Other properties==\nBy [[Euler's theorem in geometry|Euler's inequality]], the equilateral triangle has the smallest ratio ''R''/''r'' of the circumradius to the inradius of any triangle: specifically, ''R''/''r'' = 2.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Svrtan|first1=Dragutin|last2=Veljan|first2=Darko|title=Non-Euclidean versions of some classical triangle inequalities|journal=Forum Geometricorum|date=2012|volume=12|pages=197\u2013209|url=http://forumgeom.fau.edu/FG2012volume12/FG201217.pdf}}</ref>{{rp|p.198}}\n\nThe triangle of largest area of all those inscribed in a given circle is equilateral; and the triangle of smallest area of all those circumscribed around a given circle is equilateral.<ref>{{cite book|last1=D\u00f6rrie|first1=Heinrich|title=100 Great Problems of Elementary Mathematics|date=1965|publisher=Dover Publ.|pages=379\u2013380}}</ref>\n\nThe ratio of the area of the incircle to the area of an equilateral triangle, <math>\\frac{\\pi}{3\\sqrt{3}}</math>, is larger than that of any non-equilateral triangle.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Minda|first1=D.|last2=Phelps|first2=S.|title=Triangles, ellipses, and cubic polynomials|journal=American Mathematical Monthly|date=2008|volume=115|issue=October|pages=679\u2013689|jstor=27642581|doi=10.1080/00029890.2008.11920581}}</ref>{{rp|Theorem 4.1}}\n\nThe ratio of the area to the square of the perimeter of an equilateral triangle, <math>\\frac{1}{12\\sqrt{3}},</math> is larger than that for any other triangle.<ref name=Chakerian>Chakerian, G. D. \"A Distorted View of Geometry.\" Ch. 7 in ''Mathematical Plums'' (R. Honsberger, editor). Washington, DC: Mathematical Association of America, 1979: 147.</ref>\n\nIf a segment splits an equilateral triangle into two regions with equal perimeters and with areas ''A''<sub>1</sub> and ''A''<sub>2</sub>, then<ref name=Crux>{{cite web|title=Inequalities proposed in \"Crux Mathematicorum\"|url=http://hydra.nat.uni-magdeburg.de/math4u/ineq.pdf}}</ref>{{rp|p.151,#J26}}\n:<math>\\frac{7}{9} \\leq \\frac{A_1}{A_2} \\leq \\frac{9}{7}.</math>\n\nIf a triangle is placed in the [[complex plane]] with complex vertices ''z''<sub>1</sub>, ''z''<sub>2</sub>, and ''z''<sub>3</sub>, then for either non-real cube root <math>\\omega</math> of 1 the triangle is equilateral if and only if<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Dao|first1=Thanh Oai|title=Equilateral triangles and Kiepert perspectors in complex numbers|journal=Forum Geometricorum|date=2015|volume=15|pages=105\u2013114|url=http://forumgeom.fau.edu/FG2015volume15/FG201509.pdf}}</ref>{{rp|Lemma 2}}\n:<math>z_1+\\omega z_2+\\omega^2 z_3 =0.</math>\n\nGiven a point ''P'' in the interior of an equilateral triangle, the ratio of the sum of its distances from the vertices to the sum of its distances from the sides is greater than or equal to 2, equality holding when ''P'' is the centroid. In no other triangle is there a point for which this ratio is as small as 2.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lee|first1=Hojoo|title=Another proof of the Erd\u0151s\u2013Mordell Theorem|journal=Forum Geometricorum|date=2001|volume=1|pages=7\u20138|url=http://forumgeom.fau.edu/FG2001volume1/FG200102.pdf}}</ref> This is the [[Erd\u0151s\u2013Mordell inequality]]; a stronger variant of it is [[Barrow's inequality]], which replaces the perpendicular distances to the sides with the distances from ''P'' to the points where the [[angle bisector]]s of \u2220''APB'', \u2220''BPC'', and \u2220''CPA'' cross the sides (''A'', ''B'', and ''C'' being the vertices).\n\nFor any point ''P'' in the plane, with distances ''p'', ''q'', and ''t'' from the vertices ''A'', ''B'', and ''C'' respectively,<ref>Gardner, Martin, \"Elegant Triangles\", in the book ''Mathematical Circus'', 1979, p. 65.</ref>\n:<math>\\displaystyle 3(p^{4}+q^{4}+t^{4}+a^{4})=(p^{2}+q^{2}+t^{2}+a^{2})^{2}.</math>\n\nFor any point ''P'' in the plane, with distances ''p'', ''q'', and ''t'' from the vertices, <ref>{{citation|first=Mamuka|last=Meskhishvili|title=Cyclic Averages of Regular Polygons|url=https://www.gysu.org/copy-of-contact-us?fbclid=IwAR086p2tvNg3wYJy_agiwGj5gXlntfco6kpNjBurGqZcGeUjjcfxLM31xeo}}</ref>\n:<math>\\displaystyle p^{2}+q^{2}+t^{2}=3(R^{2}+L^{2})</math>\nand\n:<math>\\displaystyle p^{4}+q^{4}+t^{4}=3[(R^{2}+L^{2})^{2}+2R^{2}L^{2}],</math>\nwhere ''R''  is the circumscribed radius and ''L''   is the distance between point ''P''  and the centroid of the equilateral triangle.\n\nFor any point ''P'' on the inscribed circle of an equilateral triangle, with distances ''p'', ''q'', and ''t'' from the vertices,<ref name=De>{{cite journal|last1=De|first1=Prithwijit|title=Curious properties of the circumcircle and incircle of an equilateral triangle|journal=Mathematical Spectrum|date=2008|volume=41|issue=1|pages=32\u201335|url=http://www.appliedprobability.org/data/files/MS%20issues/Vol41_No1.pdf}}</ref>\n:<math>\\displaystyle 4(p^{2}+q^{2}+t^{2})=5a^{2}</math>\nand\n:<math>\\displaystyle 16(p^{4}+q^{4}+t^{4})=11a^{4}.</math>\n\nFor any point ''P'' on the minor arc BC of the circumcircle, with distances ''p'', ''q'', and ''t'' from A, B, and C respectively,<ref name=Posamentier>{{cite book|last1=Posamentier|first1=Alfred S.|last2=Salkind|first2=Charles T.|title=Challenging Problems in Geometry|url=https://archive.org/details/challengingprobl0000posa|url-access=registration|date=1996|publisher=Dover Publ.}}</ref>\n:<math>\\displaystyle p=q+t</math>\nand\n:<math>\\displaystyle q^{2}+qt+t^{2}=a^{2} ;</math>\n\nmoreover, if point D on side BC divides PA into segments PD and DA with DA having length ''z'' and PD having length ''y'', then <ref name=Posamentier/>{{rp|172}}\n:<math>z= \\frac{t^{2}+tq+q^2}{t+q},</math>\n\nwhich also equals <math>\\tfrac{t^{3}-q^{3}}{t^{2}-q^{2}}</math> if ''t'' \u2260 ''q''; and\n:<math>\\frac{1}{q}+\\frac{1}{t}=\\frac{1}{y},</math>\nwhich is the [[optic equation]].\n\nThere are numerous [[list of triangle inequalities|triangle inequalities]] that hold with equality if and only if the triangle is equilateral.\n\nAn equilateral triangle is the most symmetrical triangle, having 3 lines of [[reflection symmetry|reflection]] and [[rotational symmetry]] of order 3 about its center. Its [[symmetry group]] is the [[dihedral group of order 6]] ''D''<sub>3</sub>.\n\nEquilateral triangles are the only triangles whose [[Steiner inellipse]] is a circle (specifically, it is the incircle).\n\nThe integer-sided equilateral triangle is the only [[integer triangle|triangle with integer sides]] and three rational angles as measured in degrees.<ref name=CG>Conway, J. H., and Guy, R. K., \"The only rational triangle\", in ''The Book of Numbers'', 1996, Springer-Verlag, pp. 201 and 228\u2013239.</ref>\n\nThe equilateral triangle is the only acute triangle that is similar to its [[orthic triangle]] (with vertices at the feet of the [[altitude (geometry)|altitudes]]) (the [[heptagonal triangle]] being the only obtuse one).<ref name=BG>Leon Bankoff and Jack Garfunkel, \"The heptagonal triangle\", ''[[Mathematics Magazine]]'' 46 (1), January 1973, 7\u201319.</ref>{{rp|p. 19}}\n\n[[File:Viervlak-frame.jpg|thumb|right|A regular tetrahedron is made of four equilateral triangles.]]\nEquilateral triangles are found in many other geometric constructs. The intersection of circles whose centers are a radius width apart is a pair of equilateral arches, each of which can be inscribed with an equilateral triangle. They form faces of regular and uniform [[polyhedra]]. Three of the five [[Platonic solid]]s are composed of equilateral triangles. In particular, the [[tetrahedron|regular tetrahedron]] has four equilateral triangles for faces and can be considered the three-dimensional analogue of the shape. The plane can be [[Euclidean tilings by convex regular polygons|tiled]] using equilateral triangles giving the [[triangular tiling]].\n\n==Geometric construction==\n\n[[File:Equilateral triangle construction.svg|200px|thumb|right|Construction of equilateral triangle with compass and straightedge]]\n\nAn equilateral triangle is easily constructed using a [[straightedge and compass]], because 3 is a [[Fermat prime]]. Draw a straight line, and place the point of the compass on one end of the line, and swing an arc from that point to the other point of the line segment. Repeat with the other side of the line. Finally, connect the point where the two arcs intersect with each end of the line segment\n\nAn alternative method is to draw a circle with radius ''r'', place the point of the compass on the circle and draw another circle with the same radius. The two circles will intersect in two points. An equilateral triangle can be constructed by taking the two centers of the circles and either of the points of intersection.\n\nIn both methods a by-product is the formation of [[vesica piscis]].\n\nThe proof that the resulting figure is an equilateral triangle is the first proposition in Book I of [[Euclid's Elements|Euclid's ''Elements'']].\n\n[[File:Equilateral_Triangle_Inscribed_in_a_Circle.gif|center]]\n\n==Derivation of area formula==\nThe area formula <math>A = \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{4}a^2</math> in terms of side length ''a'' can be derived directly using the Pythagorean theorem or using trigonometry.\n\n===Using the Pythagorean theorem===\nThe area of a triangle is half of one side ''a'' times the height ''h'' from that side:\n:<math>A = \\frac{1}{2} ah.</math>\n\n[[File:30-60-90.svg|thumb|150px|An equilateral triangle with a side of 2 has a height of {{sqrt|3}} as the sine of 60\u00b0 is {{sqrt|3}}/2.]]\nThe legs of either right triangle formed by an altitude of the equilateral triangle are half of the base ''a'', and the hypotenuse is the side ''a'' of the equilateral triangle. The height of an equilateral triangle can be found using the [[Pythagorean theorem]]\n:<math>\\left(\\frac{a}{2}\\right)^2 + h^2 = a^2</math>\n\nso that\n:<math>h = \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2}a.</math>\n\nSubstituting ''h'' into the area formula (1/2)''ah'' gives the area formula for the equilateral triangle:\n:<math>A = \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{4}a^2.</math>\n\n===Using trigonometry===\nUsing [[trigonometry]], the area of a triangle with any two sides ''a'' and ''b'', and an angle ''C'' between them is\n:<math>A = \\frac{1}{2} ab \\sin C.</math>\n\nEach angle of an equilateral triangle is 60\u00b0, so\n:<math>A = \\frac{1}{2} ab \\sin 60^\\circ.</math>\n\nThe sine of 60\u00b0 is <math>\\tfrac{\\sqrt{3}}{2}</math>. Thus\n:<math>A = \\frac{1}{2} ab \\times \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2} = \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{4}ab = \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{4}a^2</math>\nsince all sides of an equilateral triangle are equal.\n\n==In culture and society==\nEquilateral triangles have frequently appeared in man made constructions:\n*The shape occurs in modern architecture such as the cross-section of the [[Gateway Arch]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Eero Saarinen: Shaping the Future|editor1-first=Eeva-Liisa|editor1-last=Pelkonen|editor2-first=Donald|editor2-last=Albrecht|publisher=Yale University Press|year=2006|isbn=978-0972488129|pages=[https://archive.org/details/eerosaarinenshap0000saar/page/160 160, 224, 226]|url=https://archive.org/details/eerosaarinenshap0000saar/page/160}}</ref>\n*Its applications in flags and heraldry includes the [[flag of Nicaragua]]<ref>{{cite book|title=Culture and Customs of Nicaragua|first1=Steven F.|last1=White|first2=Esthela|last2=Calder\u00f3n|publisher=Greenwood Press|year=2008|page=[https://archive.org/details/culturecustomsof00stev/page/3 3]|isbn=978-0313339943|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/culturecustomsof00stev/page/3}}</ref> and the [[flag of the Philippines]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Historical Dictionary of the Philippines|first=Artemio R.|last=Guillermo|publisher=Scarecrow Press|year=2012|isbn=978-0810872462|page=161|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wmgX9M_yETIC&pg=PA161}}</ref>\n*It is a shape of a variety of [[traffic sign|road signs]], including the [[yield sign]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Riley|first1=Michael W.|last2=Cochran|first2=David J.|last3=Ballard|first3=John L.|date=December 1982|doi=10.1177/001872088202400610|issue=6|journal=Human Factors: The Journal of the Human Factors and Ergonomics Society|pages=737\u2013742|title=An Investigation of Preferred Shapes for Warning Labels|volume=24}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Heronian triangle#Almost-equilateral Heronian triangles|Almost-equilateral Heronian triangle]]\n*[[Isosceles triangle]]\n*[[Ternary plot]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{MathWorld|title=Equilateral Triangle|urlname=EquilateralTriangle}}\n\n{{Polygons}}\n{{Polytopes}}\n\n[[Category:Triangles]]\n[[Category:Triangle geometry]]\n[[Category:Elementary shapes]]\n[[Category:Constructible polygons]]\n", "name_user": "207.255.39.154", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eCharacterizations)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equilateral_triangle"}
{"title_page": "Google Translate", "text_new": "Fu{{short description|Multilingual statistical and neural machine translation service}}\n{{update|type=|date=March 2020|reason=}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox website\n|name = Google Translate\n|logo = Google Translate logo.svg\n|logo_size = 100px\n|screenshot = Screenshot of Google Translate.png\n|collapsible = yes\n|collapsetext = Screenshot\n|caption = Google Translate homepage\n|url = {{URL|https://translate.google.com}}\n|commercial = Yes\n|type = [[Statistical machine translation|Statistical]] and [[neural machine translation]]\n|registration = Optional\n|language = <onlyinclude>109</onlyinclude> languages, see [[Google Translate#Supported languages|below]]\n|num_users = Over 500 million people daily\n|owner = [[Google]]\n|launch_date = {{start date and age|2006|4|28}} (as [[statistical machine translation]])<ref name=\"Statistical machine translation\"/><br/>{{start date and age|2016|11|15}} (as [[neural machine translation]])<ref name=\"GT_Turovsky_2016\"/>\n|current_status = Active\n}}\n'''Google Translate''' is a free multilingual [[statistical machine translation|statistical]] and [[neural machine translation]] service developed by [[Google]], to translate text and websites from one language into another. It offers a [[web application|website interface]], a [[mobile app]] for [[Android (operating system)|Android]] and [[iOS]], and an [[application programming interface]] that helps developers build [[browser extension]]s and [[application software|software application]]s. As of {{CURRENTMONTHNAME}} {{CURRENTYEAR}}, Google Translate supports {{:Google Translate}} languages at various levels and {{as of|2016|April|lc=y}}, claimed over 500 million total users, with more than 100 billion words translated daily.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.blog.google/products/translate/ten-years-of-google-translate/|title=Ten years of Google Translate|last=Turovsky|first=Barak|date=April 28, 2016|website=Google Translate Blog|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=December 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nLaunched in April 2006 as a [[statistical machine translation]] service, it used [[United Nations]] and [[European Parliament]] documents and transcripts to gather linguistic data. Rather than translating languages directly, it first translates text to English and then pivots to the target language in most of the language combinations it posits in its grid,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.teachyoubackwards.com/extras/pivot/|title=How GT Pivots through English|last=Benjamin|first=Martin|date=2019|website=Teach You Backwards|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=December 24, 2019}}</ref> with a few exceptions including Catalan-Spanish.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.teachyoubackwards.com/extras/catalan-to-spanish-translations/|title=Catalan to Spanish Translations|last=Benjamin|first=Martin|date=2019|website=Teach You Backwards|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=December 24, 2019}}</ref> During a translation, it looks for patterns in millions of documents to help decide on which words to choose and how to arrange them in the target language. Its accuracy, which has been criticized and ridiculed on several occasions,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2018/01/the-shallowness-of-google-translate/551570/|title=The Shallowness of Google Translate|last=Hofstadter|first=Douglas|date=2018-01-30|website=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> has been measured to vary greatly across languages.<ref name=\"Kamu.si\">{{Cite web|url=https://kamu.si/gt-scores|title=Source data for Teach You Backwards: An In-Depth Study of Google Translate for 103 Languages|last=Benjamin|first=Martin|date=2019|website=Teach You Backwards|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=December 24, 2019}}</ref> In November 2016, Google announced that Google Translate would switch to a [[neural machine translation]] engine - [[Google Neural Machine Translation]] (GNMT) - which translates \"whole sentences at a time, rather than just piece by piece. It uses this broader context to help it figure out the most relevant translation, which it then rearranges and adjusts to be more like a human speaking with proper grammar\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.google/products/translate/found-translation-more-accurate-fluent-sentences-google-translate/|title=Found in translation: More accurate, fluent sentences in Google Translate|date=2016-11-15|website=Google|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Originally only enabled for a few languages in 2016, GNMT is used in all {{:Google Translate}} languages in the Google Translate roster as of {{CURRENTYEAR}}, except for [[Kyrgyz language|Kyrgyz]], [[Latin]], and the [[Belarusian language|Belarusian]], [[Maltese language|Maltese]] and [[Sundanese language|Sundanese]] to other languages pairs.<ref name=\"supportedlanguages\" />\n\n== History ==\nGoogle Translate is a complementary translation service developed by Google in April 2006.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/google-translate-how-work-foreign-languages-interpreter-app-search-engine-a8406131.html|title=Google Translate: How does the search giant's multilingual interpreter actually work?|last=Sommerlad|first=Joe|date=June 19, 2018|website=INDEPENDENT|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=November 28, 2018}}</ref> It translates multiple forms of texts and media such as words, phrases and webpages.\n\nOriginally Google Translate was released as a [[statistical machine translation]] service.<ref name=\":2\" /> Translating the required text into English before translating into the selected language was a mandatory step that it had to take.<ref name=\":2\" /> Since SMT uses predictive [[algorithm]]s to translate text, it had poor grammatical accuracy. However, Google initially did not hire experts to resolve this limitation due to the ever-evolving nature of language.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn January 2010, Google has introduced an Android app and iOS version in February 2011 to serve as a portable personal interpreter.<ref name=\":2\" /> As of February 2010, it was integrated into browsers such as Chrome and was able to pronounce the text, automatically recognize words in the picture and spot unfamiliar text and languages.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn May 2014, Google acquired [[Word Lens]] to improve the quality of visual and voice translation.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.androidauthority.com/google-translate-word-lens-voice-translations-580312/|title=Google Translate just got smarter: Word Lens and instant voice translations in latest update|last=Petrovan|first=Bogdan|date=January 14, 2015|website=Android Authority|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=May 28, 2017}}</ref> It is able to scan text or a picture with one's device and have it translated instantly. Moreover, the system [[language identification|automatically identifies]] foreign languages and translates speech without requiring individuals to tap the microphone button whenever speech translation is needed.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIn November 2016, Google transitioned its translating method to a system called [[neural machine translation]].<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.argotrans.com/blog/accurate-google-translate-2018/|title=How accurate is Google Translate in 2018?|last=McGuire|first=Nick|date=July 26, 2018|website=ARGO Translation|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=November 29, 2018}}</ref> It uses [[deep learning]] techniques to translate whole sentences at a time, which it has measured to be more accurate between English and French, German, Spanish, and Chinese.<ref name=\"GoogleTranslate\">Google's Neural Machine Translation System: Bridging the Gap between Human and Machine Translation (26 Sep 2016): Yonghui Wu, Mike Schuster, Zhifeng Chen, Quoc V. Le, Mohammad Norouzi, Wolfgang Macherey, Maxim Krikun, Yuan Cao, Qin Gao, Klaus Macherey, Jeff Klingner, Apurva Shah, Melvin Johnson, Xiaobing Liu, \u0141ukasz Kaiser, Stephan Gouws, Yoshikiyo Kato, Taku Kudo, Hideto Kazawa, Keith Stevens, George Kurian, Nishant Patil, Wei Wang, Cliff Young, Jason Smith, Jason Riesa, Alex Rudnick, Oriol Vinyals, Greg Corrado, Macduff Hughes, Jeffrey Dean. https://arxiv.org/abs/1609.08144</ref> No measurement results have been provided by Google researchers for GNMT from English to other languages, other languages to English, or between language pairs that do not include English.\nAs of 2018, it translates more than 100 billion words a day.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n== Functions ==\nGoogle Translate can translate multiple forms of text and media, which includes text, speech, and text within still or moving images. Specifically, its functions include:\n\n*'''Written Words Translation:''' a function that translates written words or text to a foreign language.<ref name=\":52\">{{Cite web|url=https://support.google.com/translate/answer/6142478|title=Translate written words|date=|website=Google Translate Help|publisher=Google Inc.|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=December 1, 2016}}</ref>\n*'''Website Translation:''' a function that translates a whole webpage to selected languages<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://support.google.com/translate/answer/2534559|title=Translate webpages & documents|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Google Inc.|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=December 1, 2016}}</ref>\n*'''Document Translation:''' a function that translates a document uploaded by the users to selected languages. The documents should be in the form of: .doc, .docx, .odf, .pdf, .ppt, .pptx, .ps, .rtf, .txt, .xls, .xlsx.<ref name=\":0\" />\n*'''Speech Translation:''' a function that instantly translates spoken language into the selected foreign language.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://support.google.com/translate/answer/6142468|title=Translate by speech|last=|first=|date=|website=Google Translate Help|publisher=Google Inc.|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=December 1, 2016}}</ref>\n*'''Mobile App Translation:''' in 2018, Google Translate has introduced its new feature called \u201cTap to Translate,\u201d which made instant translation accessible inside any app without exiting or switching it.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/intl/en/about/|title=About - Google Translate|date=|website=Google Translate|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=July 9, 2017}}</ref>\n*'''Image Translation:''' a function that identifies text in a picture taken by the users and translates text on the screen instantly by images.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://support.google.com/translate/answer/6142483|title=Translate images|date=|website=Google Translate Help|publisher=Google Inc.|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=November 20, 2018}}</ref>\n*'''Handwritten Translation:''' a function that translates language that are handwritten on the phone screen or drawn on a virtual keyboard without the support of a keyboard.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://support.google.com/translate/answer/6142469|title=Translate with handwriting or virtual keyboard|date=|website=Google Translate Help|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=December 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nFor most of its features, Google Translate provides the pronunciation, dictionary, and listening to translation. Additionally, Google Translate has introduced its own Translate app, so translation is available with a mobile phone in offline mode.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n== Features ==\nGoogle Translate produces approximations across languages of multiple forms of text and media, including text, speech, websites, or text on display in still or live video images.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\"googlehelp\">{{cite web|title=Google Translate Help|url=https://support.google.com/translate|publisher=Google Inc.|accessdate=June 4, 2014}}</ref> For some languages, Google Translate can synthesize speech from text,<ref name=\":52\" /> and in certain pairs it is possible to highlight specific corresponding words and phrases between the source and target text. Results are sometimes shown with dictional information below the translation box, but it is not a dictionary<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://teachyoubackwards.com/how-to-use-google-translate/#dictionary|title=When and How to Use Google Translate|last=Benjamin|first=Martin|date=2019|website=Teach You Backwards|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=December 25, 2019}}</ref> and has been shown to invent translations in all languages for words it does not recognize.<ref name=\"Ooga Booga\">{{Cite web|url=https://teachyoubackwards.com/qualitative-analysis/#ooga-booga|title=Ooga Booga: Better than a Dictionary|last=Benjamin|first=Martin|date=2019|website=Teach You Backwards|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=December 25, 2019}}</ref> If \"Detect language\" is selected, text in an unknown language can be automatically identified. In the web interface, users can suggest alternate translations, such as for technical terms, or correct mistakes. These suggestions may be included in future updates to the translation process. If a user enters a [[URL]] in the source text, Google Translate will produce a [[hyperlink]] to a machine translation of the website.<ref name=\":0\" /> Users can save translation proposals in a \"phrasebook\" for later use.<ref>{{cite web|title=Save translations in a phrasebook|url=https://support.google.com/translate/answer/6142480|website=Google Translate Help|publisher=Google Inc.|accessdate=May 28, 2017}}</ref> For some languages, text can be entered via an [[virtual keyboard|on-screen keyboard]], through [[handwriting recognition]], or [[speech recognition]].<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> It is possible to enter searches in a source language that are first translated to a destination language allowing one to browse and interpret results from the selected destination language in the source language.\n\nTexts written in the [[Greek alphabet|Greek]], [[Devanagari]], [[Cyrillic script|Cyrillic]] and [[Arabic script|Arabic]] scripts can be transliterated automatically from phonetic equivalents written in the [[Latin alphabet]]. The browser version of Google Translate provides the read phonetically option for Japanese to English conversion. The same option is not available on the paid API version.\n\n[[File:Google Eng Accent.png|thumb|Accent of English that the \"text-to-speech\" audio of Google Translate of each country uses{{legend|#22B14C|British (Received Pronunciation) (female)}}{{legend|#F0F|General American (female)}}{{legend|#FFF200|General Australian (female)}}{{legend|black|No Google translate service}}]]\nMany of the more popular languages have a \"text-to-speech\" audio function that is able to read back a text in that language, up to a few dozen words or so. In the case of [[pluricentric language]]s, the accent depends on the region: for [[English language|English]], in the [[Americas]], most of the [[Asia-Pacific]] and [[West Asia]], the audio uses a female [[General American English|General American]] accent, whereas in [[Europe]], [[Hong Kong]], [[Malaysia]], [[Singapore]], [[Guyana]] and all other parts of the world, a female [[British English|British]] ([[Received Pronunciation]]) accent is used, except for a special [[Australian English|General Australian]] accent used in [[Australia]], [[New Zealand]] and [[Norfolk Island]]; for [[Spanish language|Spanish]], in the [[Americas]], a [[Spanish language in the Americas|Latin American]] accent is used, while in the other parts of the world, a [[Castilian Spanish|Castilian]] accent is used; [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] uses a [[Brazilian Portuguese|S\u00e3o Paulo]] accent around the world, except in [[Portugal]], where [[European Portuguese|their native accent]] is used. Some less widely spoken languages use the open-source [[eSpeak]] synthesizer for their speech; producing a robotic, awkward voice that may be difficult to understand.\n\n=== Browser integration ===\nGoogle Translate is available in some [[web browser]]s as an optional downloadable extension that can run the translation engine, which allow right-click command access to the translation service.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/search?q=Google+Translate|title=Search Add-ons :: Add-ons for Firefox|publisher=Mozilla|accessdate=August 7, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Google Translate|url=https://chrome.google.com/webstore/detail/google-translate/aapbdbdomjkkjkaonfhkkikfgjllcleb|work=[[Chrome Web Store]]|accessdate=December 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Roberto|last=Baldwin|title=Google introduces Google Translate Chrome Extension for inline translations of text|url=https://thenextweb.com/google/2014/10/16/google-introduces-google-translate-chrome-extension-inline-translations-text/|website=The Next Web|date=October 16, 2014|accessdate=May 28, 2017}}</ref> In February 2010, Google Translate was integrated into the [[Google Chrome]] browser by default, for optional automatic webpage translation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ghacks.net/2010/02/07/google-translate-integrated-in-google-chrome-5/|title=Google Translate Integrated in Google Chrome 5|first=Martin|last=Brinkmann|publisher=Ghacks.net|date=February 7, 2010|accessdate=December 22, 2011}}</ref><ref>[http://stuff.techwhack.com/8388-google-chrome-5-translate Google Chrome 5 features an integrated Google Translate service] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100726134705/http://stuff.techwhack.com/8388-google-chrome-5-translate|date=July 26, 2010}} February 15, 2010. ''stuff.techwhack.com''</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Robin|last=Wauters|title=Rant: Google Translate Toolbar In Chrome 5 Needs An 'Off' Button|url=https://techcrunch.com/2010/02/14/google-chrome-5-translate-toolbar/|website=[[TechCrunch]]|publisher=[[AOL]]|date=February 14, 2010|accessdate=May 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Mobile app ===\n{{Infobox software\n|name = Google Translate\n|logo = Google Translate Icon.png\n|screenshot = Google Translate iOS app screenshot.png\n|caption = A screenshot of the iOS app of Google Translate, showing an English translation of \"Coffee\" to Simplified Chinese \"\u5496\u5561\" or \"K\u0101f\u0113i\"\n|collapsible = yes\n|developer = [[Google]]\n|released = {{start date and age|2010|01|01}} (for Android)<br />{{start date and age|2011|02|08}} (for iOS)\n|ver layout = stacked\n|platform = {{hlist|[[Android (operating system)|Android]] [[Android Lollipop|5.0]] and later|[[iOS]] [[IOS 11|11]] and later}}\n|size = 20.74 [[megabyte|MB]] (Android)<br />70.9 MB (iOS)\n|language = {{:Google Translate}} languages, see [[Google Translate#Supported languages|below]]\n|genre = [[Statistical machine translation|Statistical]] and [[neural machine translation]]\n|website = {{URL|m.translate.google.com}}\n}}\nThe Google Translate app for [[Android (operating system)|Android]] and [[iOS]] supports {{:Google Translate}} languages and can propose translations for 37 languages via photo, 32 via voice in \"conversation mode\", and 27 via live video imagery in \"augmented reality mode\".<ref>{{cite web|first=Ariha|last=Setalvad|title=Google Translate adds 20 new languages to video text translation|url=https://www.theverge.com/2015/7/29/9061135/google-translate-update-new-languages-word-lens|website=[[The Verge]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|date=July 29, 2015|accessdate=March 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Android app was released in January 2010, while an [[HTML5]] [[web application]] was released for iOS users in August 2008,<ref>{{cite web|first=Allen|last=Hutchison|title=Google Translate now for iPhone|url=http://googlemobile.blogspot.com/2008/08/google-translate-now-for-iphone.html|website=Google Mobile Blog|date=August 7, 2008|accessdate=March 23, 2017}}</ref> followed by a native app on February 8, 2011.<ref name=\"Zhu\">{{cite web|first=Wenzhang|last=Zhu|title=Introducing the Google Translate app for iPhone|url=https://googleblog.blogspot.com/2011/02/introducing-google-translate-app-for.html|website=Official Google Blog|date=February 8, 2011|accessdate=March 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe application supports 103 languages and voice input for 45 languages.<ref name=\"supportedlanguages\" /> It is available for devices running Android 2.1 and above and can be downloaded by searching for \"Google Translate\" in [[Google Play]].\n\nThe current Google Translate app is compatible with [[iPhone]], [[iPad]], and [[iPod Touch]] updated to iOS 7.0+.<ref name=\"iTunes\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/google-translate/id414706506?mt=8|title=Google Translate on iTunes|work=Google|accessdate=July 29, 2015}}</ref> It accepts voice input for 15 languages and allows translation of a word or phrase into one of more than 50 languages. Translations can be spoken out loud in 23 different languages.<ref name=\"Zhu\" />\n\nA January 2011 Android version experimented with a \"Conversation Mode\" that aims to allow users to communicate fluidly with a nearby person in another language.<ref>{{cite web|first=Mark|last=Hachman|title=Google Translate's New 'Conversation Mode': Hands On|url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2375655,00.asp|website=[[PC Magazine]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|date=January 12, 2011|accessdate=May 28, 2017}}</ref> Originally limited to English and Spanish, the feature received support for 12 new languages, still in testing, the following October.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gigaom.com/2011/10/13/google-translate-conversation-mode-adds-14-languages/|title=Google Translate conversation mode expands to 14 languages|author=Ryan Kim|publisher=GigaOM|date=October 13, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Chris|last=Velazco|title=Google Translate For Android Gets Upgraded \"Conversation Mode\"|url=https://techcrunch.com/2011/10/13/google-translate-for-android-gets-upgraded-conversation-mode/|website=[[TechCrunch]]|publisher=[[AOL]]|date=October 13, 2011|accessdate=May 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe 'Camera input' functionality allows users to take a photograph of a document, signboard, etc. Google Translate recognises the text from the image using [[optical character recognition]] (OCR) technology and gives the translation. Camera input is not available for all languages.\n\nIn January 2015, the apps gained the ability to propose translations of physical signs in real time using the device's camera, as a result of Google's acquisition of the [[Word Lens]] app.<ref>{{cite web|first=Barak|last=Turovsky|title=Hallo, hola, ol\u00e1 to the new, more powerful Google Translate app|url=https://googleblog.blogspot.com/2015/01/hallo-hola-ola-more-powerful-translate.html|website=Official Google Blog|date=January 14, 2015|accessdate=March 23, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Jon|last=Russell|title=Google Translate Now Does Real-Time Voice And Sign Translations On Mobile|url=https://techcrunch.com/2015/01/14/amaaaaaazing/|website=[[TechCrunch]]|publisher=[[AOL]]|date=January 14, 2015|accessdate=May 28, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" /> The original January launch only supported seven languages, but a July update added support for 20 new languages, with the release of a new implementation that utilizes [[convolutional neural network]]s, and also enhanced the speed and quality of Conversation Mode translations ([[augmented reality]]).<ref>{{cite web|first=Barak|last=Turovsky|title=See the world in your language with Google Translate|url=https://googleblog.blogspot.com/2015/07/see-world-in-your-language-with-google.html|website=Official Google Blog|date=July 29, 2015|accessdate=March 23, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Otavio|last=Good|title=How Google Translate squeezes deep learning onto a phone|url=https://research.googleblog.com/2015/07/how-google-translate-squeezes-deep.html|website=Google Research Blog|date=July 29, 2015|accessdate=March 23, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Andrew|last=Gush|title=Google Translate adds video translation support for 25 more languages|url=http://www.androidauthority.com/google-translate-video-translation-629893/|website=Android Authority|date=July 29, 2015|accessdate=May 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Drew|last=Olanoff|title=Google Translate's App Now Instantly Translates Printed Text In 27 Languages|url=https://techcrunch.com/2015/07/29/google-translates-app-now-instantly-translates-printed-text-in-27-languages/|website=[[TechCrunch]]|publisher=[[AOL]]|date=July 29, 2015|accessdate=May 28, 2017}}</ref> The feature was subsequently renamed Instant Camera. The technology underlying Instant Camera combines image processing and optical character recognition, then attempts to produce cross-language equivalents using standard Google Translate estimations for the text as it is perceived.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://teachyoubackwards.com/introduction/#instant-camera|title=Instant Camera Translation|last=Benjamin|first=Martin|date=2019|website=Teach You Backwards|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=December 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn May 11, 2016, Google introduced ''Tap to Translate'' for Google Translate for Android. Upon highlighting text in an app that is in a foreign language, Translate will pop up inside of the app and offer translations.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Google Translate now works inside any app on Android|last=Kastrenakes|first=Jacob|url=http://www.theverge.com/2016/5/11/11656900/tap-to-translate-google-translate-inside-any-android-app|publisher=The Verge|accessdate=May 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== API ===\nOn May 26, 2011, Google announced that the Google Translate [[application programming interface|API]] for [[software development|software developer]]s had been deprecated and would cease functioning.<ref name=\"Feldman\">{{cite web|first=Adam|last=Feldman|title=Spring cleaning for some of our APIs|url=http://googlecode.blogspot.com/2011/05/spring-cleaning-for-some-of-our-apis.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110528125302/http://googlecode.blogspot.com/2011/05/spring-cleaning-for-some-of-our-apis.html|work=Official Google Code Blog|date=May 26, 2011|archivedate=May 28, 2011|accessdate=December 11, 2016}}</ref> The Translate API page stated the reason as \"substantial economic burden caused by extensive abuse\" with an end date set for December 1, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title=Google Translate API (Deprecated)|url=http://code.google.com/apis/language/translate/overview.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110822200912/http://code.google.com/apis/language/translate/overview.html|work=Google Code|archivedate=August 22, 2011|accessdate=December 11, 2016}}</ref> In response to public pressure, Google announced in June 2011 that the API would continue to be available as a paid service.<ref name=\"Feldman\"/><ref name=\"GTS Blog\">{{cite web|url=http://blog.gts-translation.com/2011/05/27/breaking-news-google-to-shut-down-translate-api/|title=Google cancels plan to shutdown Translate API. To start charging for translations|date=June 4, 2011|accessdate=June 4, 2011|url-status=|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110531023043/http://blog.gts-translation.com/2011/05/27/breaking-news-google-to-shut-down-translate-api/|archivedate=May 31, 2011}}</ref>\n\nBecause the API was used in numerous third-party websites and apps, the original decision to deprecate it led some developers to criticize Google and question the viability of using Google APIs in their products.<ref name=\"Wong\">{{cite web|first=George|last=Wong|title=Google gets rid of APIs for Translate and other services|url=http://www.ubergizmo.com/2011/05/google-rid-translate-api/|publisher=UberGizmo|date=May 27, 2011|accessdate=May 28, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Burnette\">{{cite web|first=Ed|last=Burnette|title=Google pulls the rug out from under web service API developers, nixes Google Translate and 17 others|url=http://www.zdnet.com/article/google-pulls-the-rug-out-from-under-web-service-api-developers-nixes-google-translate-and-17-others/|publisher=[[ZDNet]]|date=May 27, 2011|accessdate=May 28, 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== Google Assistant ===\nGoogle Translate also provides translations for [[Google Assistant]] and the devices that Google Assistant runs on such as [[Google Home]] and [[Pixel Buds]].\n\n== Supported languages ==\nThe following {{:Google Translate}} languages are supported by Google Translate as of {{CURRENTMONTHNAME}} {{CURRENTYEAR}}.<ref name=\"supportedlanguages\">{{cite web|title=See which features work with each language|url=https://translate.google.com/intl/en/about/languages/|accessdate=July 9, 2017}}</ref> Chinese (Simplified) and Chinese (Traditional) refer to two different writing systems for the same language, so the actual total number of languages in the roster is 108.\n<!-- Please don't add any languages that aren't on the Google Translate homepage yet. -->\n{{-}}\n{{div col|colwidth=16em}}\n#[[Afrikaans]]\n#[[Albanian language|Albanian]]\n#[[Amharic]]\n#[[Arabic]]\n#[[Armenian language|Armenian]]\n#[[Azerbaijani language|Azerbaijani]]\n#[[Basque language|Basque]]\n#[[Belarusian language|Belarusian]]\n#[[Bengali language|Bengali]]\n#[[Bosnian language|Bosnian]]\n#[[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]]\n#[[Burmese language|Burmese]]\n#[[Catalan language|Catalan]]\n#[[Cebuano language|Cebuano]]\n#[[Chewa language|Chewa]]\n#[[Standard Chinese|Chinese (Simplified)]]\n#[[Standard Chinese|Chinese (Traditional)]]\n#[[Corsican language|Corsican]]\n#[[Croatian language|Croatian]]\n#[[Czech language|Czech]]\n#[[Danish language|Danish]]\n#[[Dutch language|Dutch]]\n#[[English language|English]]\n#[[Esperanto]]\n#[[Estonian language|Estonian]]\n#[[Filipino language|Filipino]]\n#[[Finnish language|Finnish]]\n#[[French language|French]]\n#[[Galician language|Galician]]\n#[[Georgian language|Georgian]]\n#[[German language|German]]\n#[[Greek language|Greek