 -->\n##English to and from [[Italian language|Italian]]\n#4th stage <!-- date to be filled in -->\n##English to and from [[Standard Chinese|Chinese (Simplified)]]\n##English to and from [[Japanese language|Japanese]]\n##English to and from [[Korean language|Korean]]\n#5th stage (launched April 28, 2006)<ref name=\"Statistical machine translation\"/>\n##English to and from [[Arabic]]\n#6th stage (launched December 16, 2006)\n##English to and from [[Russian language|Russian]]\n#7th stage (launched February 9, 2007)\n##English to and from [[Standard Chinese|Chinese (Traditional)]]\n##[[Standard Chinese|Chinese (Simplified to and from Traditional)]]\n#8th stage (all 25 language pairs use Google's machine translation system) (launched October 22, 2007)\n##English to and from [[Dutch language|Dutch]]\n##English to and from [[Greek language|Greek]]\n#9th stage <!-- date to be filled in -->\n##English to and from [[Hindi]]\n#10th stage (as of this stage, translation can be done between any two languages, using English as an intermediate step, if needed) (launched May 8, 2008)\n##[[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]]\n##[[Croatian language|Croatian]]\n##[[Czech language|Czech]]\n##[[Danish language|Danish]]\n##[[Finnish language|Finnish]]\n##[[Norwegian language|Norwegian]]\n##[[Polish language|Polish]]\n##[[Romanian language|Romanian]]\n##[[Swedish language|Swedish]]\n#11th stage (launched September 25, 2008)\n##[[Catalan language|Catalan]]\n##[[Filipino language|Filipino]]\n##[[Hebrew language|Hebrew]]\n##[[Indonesian language|Indonesian]]\n##[[Latvian language|Latvian]]\n##[[Lithuanian language|Lithuanian]]\n##[[Serbian language|Serbian]]\n##[[Slovak language|Slovak]]\n##[[Slovene language|Slovene]]\n##[[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]]\n##[[Vietnamese language|Vietnamese]]\n#12th stage (launched January 30, 2009)\n##[[Albanian language|Albanian]]\n##[[Estonian language|Estonian]]\n##[[Galician language|Galician]]\n##[[Hungarian language|Hungarian]]\n##[[Maltese language|Maltese]]\n##[[Thai language|Thai]]\n##[[Turkish language|Turkish]]\n#13th stage (launched June 19, 2009)\n##[[Persian language|Persian]]\n#14th stage (launched August 24, 2009)\n##[[Afrikaans]]\n##[[Belarusian language|Belarusian]]\n##[[Icelandic language|Icelandic]]\n##[[Irish language|Irish]]\n##[[Macedonian language|Macedonian]]\n##[[Malay language|Malay]]\n##[[Swahili language|Swahili]]\n##[[Welsh language|Welsh]]\n##[[Yiddish]]\n#15th stage (launched November 19, 2009)\n##The Beta stage is finished. Users can now choose to have the [[romanization]] written for Belarusian, Bulgarian, Chinese, Greek, Hindi, Japanese, Korean, Russian, Thai and Ukrainian. For translations from Arabic, Hindi and Persian, the user can enter a Latin transliteration of the text and the text will be transliterated to the native script for these languages as the user is typing. The text can now be read by a [[speech synthesis|text-to-speech]] program in English, French, German and Italian.\n#16th stage (launched January 30, 2010)\n##[[Haitian Creole]]\n#17th stage (launched April 2010)\n##Speech program launched in Hindi and Spanish.\n#18th stage (launched May 5, 2010)\n##Speech program launched in Afrikaans, Albanian, Catalan, Chinese (Mandarin), Croatian, Czech, Danish, Dutch, Finnish, Greek, Hungarian, Icelandic, Indonesian, Latvian, Macedonian, Norwegian, Polish, Portuguese, Romanian, Russian, Serbian, Slovak, Swahili, Swedish, Turkish, Vietnamese and Welsh (based on [[eSpeak]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://googleblog.blogspot.com/2010/05/giving-voice-to-more-languages-on.html|title=Giving a voice to more languages on Google Translate|last=Henderson|first=Fergus|work=Google Blog|date=November 5, 2010|accessdate=December 22, 2011}}</ref>\n#19th stage (launched May 13, 2010)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://translate.googleblog.com/2010/05/five-more-languages-on.html|title=Five more languages on Google Translate|work=Google Translate Blog|date=May 13, 2010|accessdate=December 22, 2011}}</ref>\n##[[Armenian language|Armenian]]\n##[[Azerbaijani language|Azerbaijani]]\n##[[Basque language|Basque]]\n##[[Georgian language|Georgian]]\n##[[Urdu]]\n#20th stage (launched June 2010)\n##Provides romanization for Arabic.\n#21st stage (launched September 2010)\n##Allows phonetic typing for Arabic, Greek, Hindi, Persian, Russian, Serbian and Urdu.\n##[[Latin]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://googleblog.blogspot.com/2010/09/veni-vidi-verba-verti.html|title=Veni, Vidi, Verba Verti|author=Jakob Uszkoreit, Ingeniarius Programmandi|work=Google Blog|date=September 30, 2010|accessdate=December 22, 2011}}</ref>\n#22nd stage (launched December 2010)\n##Romanization of Arabic removed.\n##Spell check added.\n##For some languages, Google replaced text-to-speech synthesizers from eSpeak's robot voice to native speaker's nature voice technologies made by [[SVOX]]<ref>[http://www.svox.com/News-Items-Google-picks-SVOX-for-Translate-and-Dictionary-services-.aspx SVOX] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101226044925/http://www.svox.com/News-Items-Google-picks-SVOX-for-Translate-and-Dictionary-services-.aspx|date=December 26, 2010}}</ref> (Chinese, Czech, Danish, Dutch, Finnish, Greek, Hungarian, Norwegian, Polish, Portuguese, Russian, Swedish, Turkish), and also the old versions of French, German, Italian and Spanish; Latin uses the same synthesizer as Italian.\n##Speech program launched in Arabic, Japanese and Korean.\n#23rd stage (launched January 2011)\n##Choice of different translations for a word.\n#24th stage (launched June 2011)\n##5 new Indic languages (in alpha) and a transliterated input method:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://translate.googleblog.com/2011/06/google-translate-welcomes-you-to-indic.html|title=Google Translate welcomes you to the Indic web|work=Google Translate Blog}}</ref>\n##[[Bengali language|Bengali]]\n##[[Gujarati language|Gujarati]]\n##[[Kannada]]\n##[[Tamil language|Tamil]]\n##[[Telugu language|Telugu]]\n#25th stage (launched July 2011)\n##Translation rating in